{"title_page": "Border reivers", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{redirect|Reivers|the actor|David Reivers|articles with similar names|The Reivers (disambiguation)}}\n{{engvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n[[File:Reivers raid on Gilnockie Tower.jpg|thumb|Reivers at [[Gilnockie Tower]], from a 19th-century print|alt=|366x366px]]\n[[File:Wat o' Harden's horn.JPG|thumb|273x273px|Notorious raider, [[Walter Scott of Harden]]'s horn, noted in a poem called \"The Reiver's Wedding\" by [[Walter Scott|Sir Walter Scott]]:\n\n\n\"He took a bugle frae his side,\n\nWith names carved o'er and o'er,\n\nFull many a chief of meikle pride,\n\nThat Border bugle bore.\"\n\n\n(A fragment of the full poem.)]]\n'''Border reivers''' were [[Cattle raiding|raiders]] along the [[Anglo-Scottish border]] from the late 13th century to the beginning of the 17th century. Their ranks consisted of both [[Scotland|Scottish]] and [[England|English]] people, and they raided the entire [[Border country]] without regard to their victims' nationality. Their heyday was in the last hundred years of their existence, during the time of the [[House of Stuart]] in the [[Kingdom of Scotland]] and the [[House of Tudor]] in the [[Kingdom of England]]\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Dryhope Tower - geograph.org.uk - 195093.jpg|thumb|278x278px|[[Dryhope Tower]] built in the 1500s for protection against the reivers]]\nScotland and England were frequently at war during the late [[Middle Ages]]. During these wars, the livelihood of the people on the Borders was devastated by the contending armies. Even when the countries were not formally at war, tension remained high, and royal authority in either or both kingdoms was often weak, particularly in remote locations. The difficulty and uncertainties of basic human survival meant that communities and/or people kindred to each other would seek security through group strength and cunning. They would attempt to improve their livelihoods at their nominal enemies' expense, enemies who were frequently also just trying to survive. Loyalty to a feeble or distant monarch and reliance on the effectiveness of the law usually made people a target for [[Raid (military)|depredations]] rather than conferring any security.\n\nThere were other factors which promoted a [[Predation|predatory]] mode of living in the Borders. A system of inheritance called [[gavelkind]] meant that estates, and particularly land, were divided equally between all sons on a man's death; although this was considered more fair than [[primogeniture]], it also meant that many people owned insufficient land to survive.<ref name=Durham5>Durham & McBride, p.5</ref> Also, much of the border region is mountainous or open moorland, unsuitable for arable farming but good for grazing. Livestock was easily rustled and driven back to raiders' territory by mounted reivers who knew the country well. The raiders also often removed easily portable household goods or valuables, and took prisoners for ransom.\n\nThe attitudes of the English and Scottish governments towards the border families alternated from indulgence and even encouragement, as these fierce families served as the first line of defence against invasion across the border, to draconian and indiscriminate punishment when their lawlessness became intolerable to the authorities.\n\n''Reive'', a noun meaning raid, comes from the Middle English (Scots) ''reifen.'' The verb ''reave'' meaning \"plunder, rob\", a closely related word, comes from the Middle English ''reven''. There also exists a [[Northumbrian English|Northumbrian]] and [[Scots language|Scots]] verb ''reifen.''  All three derive from [[Old English]] ''r\u0113afian'' which means \"to rob, plunder, pillage\".<ref>[http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/Reiver merriam-webster.com]</ref> The corresponding verb in Dutch is \"(be)roven\", and \"(be)rauben\" in German.\n\n==Nature==\n[[File:WatHarden.jpg|thumb|right|''[[Walter Scott of Harden|Auld Wat of Harden]]'' by [[Tom Scott (painter)|Tom Scott]]. A romanticised image of a notorious raider, Walter Scott of Harden.]]\nThe reivers were both English and Scottish and raided both sides of the border impartially, so long as the people they raided had no powerful protectors and no connection to their own kin. Their activities, although usually within a day's ride of the border, extended both north and south of their main haunts. English raiders were reported to have hit the outskirts of [[Edinburgh]], and Scottish raids were known as far south as [[Yorkshire]]. The largest of these was [[The Great Raid of 1322]], during the [[Scottish Wars of Independence]], where it reached as far south as [[Chorley]]. The main raiding season ran through the early winter months, when the nights were longest and the cattle and horses fat from having spent the summer grazing. The numbers involved in a raid might range from a few dozen to organised campaigns involving up to three thousand riders.<ref>George MacDonald Fraser, p.38</ref>\n\nWhen raiding, or riding, as it was termed, the reivers rode light on hardy nags or ponies renowned for the ability to pick their way over the boggy moss lands (see: [[Galloway pony]], [[Hobelar]]). The original dress of a [[Northumbrian tartan|shepherd's plaid]] was later replaced by light armour such as [[brigandine]]s or [[Jack of plate|jacks of plate]] (a type of sleeveless [[doublet (clothing)|doublet]] into which small plates of steel were stitched), and metal helmets such as [[burgonet]]s or [[Morion (helmet)|morions]]; hence their nickname of the \"steel bonnets\". They were armed with light lances and small shields, and sometimes also with [[longbow]]s, or light [[crossbow]]s, known as \"latches\", or later on in their history with one or more pistols. They invariably also carried [[sword]]s and [[dirk]]s.\n\n==Borderers as soldiers==\nBorder reivers were sometimes in demand as [[mercenaries|mercenary soldiers]], owing to their recognized skills as light [[cavalry]].  Reivers sometimes served in English or Scottish armies in the [[Low Countries]] and in Ireland, often to avoid having harsher penalties enacted upon themselves and their families. Reivers fighting as levied soldiers played important roles in the battles at [[Battle of Flodden|Flodden]] and [[Battle of Solway Moss|Solway Moss]]. After meeting one reiver (the [[Walter Scott, 1st Lord Scott of Buccleuch|''Bold Buccleugh'']]), [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth I]] is quoted as having said that \"with ten thousand such men, [[James VI and I|James VI]] could shake any throne in Europe.\" \n\nThese borderers proved difficult to control, however, within larger national armies. They were already in the habit of claiming any nationality or none, depending on who was asking and where they perceived the individual advantage to be. Many had relatives on both sides of Scottish-English conflicts despite prevailing laws against international marriage. They could be badly-behaved in camp, seeing fellow soldiers as sources of plunder. As warriors more loyal to clans than to nations, their commitment to the work was always in doubt. At battles such as [[Battle of Ancrum Moor|Ancrum Moor]] in Scotland in 1545, borderers changed sides in mid-combat to curry favour with the likely victors. At the [[Battle of Pinkie Cleugh]] in 1547, an observer ([[William Patten (historian)|William Patten]]) noticed Scottish and English borderers chatting with each other, then putting on a spirited show of combat once they knew they had been spotted.<ref>Moffat</ref>\n\n==Dwellings and fortifications==\n[[File:Black Middens Bastle - geograph.org.uk - 1224658.jpg|left|thumb|[[Black Middens Bastle House]], a surviving bastle house near [[Kielder Water]] in Northumberland]]\n\nThe inhabitants of the Borders had to live in a state of constant alert, and for self-protection, they built fortified [[Tower houses in Britain and Ireland|tower house]]s.\n\nIn the very worst periods of warfare, people were unable to construct more than crude turf cabins, the destruction of which would be little loss. When times allowed however, they built houses designed as much for defence as shelter. The [[bastle house]] was a stout two-storeyed building. The lower floor was used to keep the most valuable livestock and horses. The upper storey housed the people, and often could be reached only by an external ladder which was pulled up at night or if danger threatened. The stone walls were up to {{convert|3|ft|m|1}} thick, and the roof was of slate or stone tiles. Only narrow arrow slits provided light and ventilation.<ref>Durham & McBride, p.24</ref> Such dwellings could not be set on fire, and while they could be captured, for example by smoking out the defenders with fires of damp straw or using scaling ladders to reach the roof, they were usually not worth the time and effort.\n\n[[Peel tower]]s (also spelled pele towers) were usually three-storeyed buildings, constructed specifically for defensive purposes by the authorities, or for prestigious individuals such as the heads of clans. [[Smailholm Tower]] is one of many surviving peel towers. Like bastle houses, they were very strongly constructed for defence. If necessary, they could be temporarily abandoned and stuffed full of smouldering turf to prevent an enemy (such as a government army) destroying them with gunpowder.<ref>Durham & McBride, p.23</ref>\n\nPeel towers and bastle houses were often surrounded by a stone wall known as a barmkin, inside which cattle and other livestock were kept overnight.\n\n==Law and order==\n[[File:Late-medieval jack, National Museum of Scotland collection.jpg|thumb|A leather jack of the kind worn by reivers in the 16th century]]\nDuring periods of nominal peace, a special body of [[customary law]], known as [[March law (Anglo-Scottish border)|March law]] or Border law, grew up to deal with the situation. Under border law, a person who had been raided had the right to mount a counter-raid within six days, even across the border, to recover his goods. This \"hot trod\" had to proceed with \"hound and horne, hew and cry\",<ref>Durham & McBride, p. 20.</ref> making a racket and carrying a piece of burning turf on a spear point to openly announce their purpose, to distinguish themselves from unlawful raiders proceeding covertly. They might use a [[sleuth hound]] (also known as a \"slew dogge\") to follow raiders' tracks. These dogs were valuable, and part of the established forces (on the English side of the border, at least).<ref>George MacDonald Fraser, pp. 95\u201396</ref> Any person meeting this counter-raid was required to ride along and offer such help as he could, on pain of being considered complicit with the raiders. The \"cold trod\" mounted after six days required official sanction. Officers such as the Deputy Warden of the English West March had the specific duty of \"following the trod\".<ref>George MacDonald Fraser, p. 215 fn.</ref>\n\nBoth sides of the border were divided into [[Scottish Marches|Marches]], each under a [[Lord Warden of the Marches|march warden]]. The march wardens' various duties included the maintenance of patrols, watches and garrisons to deter raiding from the other kingdom. On occasion, march wardens could make ''warden roades'' to recover loot, and to make a point to raiders and officials.\n\nThe march wardens also had the duty of maintaining such justice and equity as was possible. The respective kingdoms' march wardens would meet at appointed times along the border itself to settle claims against people on their side of the border by people from the other kingdom. These occasions, known as \"Days of Truce\", were much like fairs, with entertainment and much socialising. For reivers it was an opportunity to meet (lawfully) with relatives or friends normally separated by the border. It was not unknown for violence to break out even at such truce days.\n\nMarch wardens (and the lesser officers such as keepers of fortified places) were rarely effective at maintaining the law. The Scottish wardens were usually borderers themselves, and were complicit in raiding. They almost invariably showed favour to their own kindred, which caused jealousy and even hatred among other Scottish border families. Many English officers were from southern counties in England and often could not command the loyalty or respect of their locally recruited subordinates or the local population. Local officers such as [[Sir John Forster]], who was Warden of the Middle March for almost 35 years, became quite as well known for venality as his most notorious Scottish counterparts.<ref>George MacDonald Fraser, pp.139\u2013140</ref>\n\nBy the death of [[Elizabeth I of England]], things had come to such a pitch along the border that the English government considered re-fortifying and rebuilding [[Hadrian's Wall]].<ref>George MacDonald Fraser, p.210</ref> When Elizabeth died, there was an especially violent outbreak of raiding known as \"Ill Week\", resulting from the convenient belief that the laws of a kingdom were suspended between the death of a sovereign and the proclamation of the successor.<ref>George MacDonald Fraser, p.360</ref> Upon his accession to the English throne, [[James I of England|James VI]] of Scotland (who became James I of England) moved hard against the reivers, abolishing border law and the very term \"Borders\" in favour of \"Middle [[Shire]]s,\" and dealing out stern justice to reivers.\n\n===Legislation===\nIn 1606 an act (4 Jas. 1. c. 1) to assist the recent [[Union of the Crowns]] was enacted; it was [[long title]]d ''An act for the utter abolition of all memory of hostility, and the dependence thereof, between England and Scotland, and for repressing of occasions of disorders, and disorders in time to come''. The act repealed nine English laws enacted over the previous centuries and considered hostile to Scotland; the repeal became effective when 13 Scottish laws considered hostile to England had been repealed.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge50britgoog#page/n226/mode/2up Statutes at Large - Volume 7 - 39 Elizabeth to 12 Charles II - 1597-8 to 1660], p.195</ref> Three years later an act (7 Jas. 1 c. 1) dealing with criminal law in the border region was enacted; it was long titled ''An act for the better execution of justice, and suppressing of criminal offenders, in the north parts of the kingdom of England.'' To deal with cross-border flight, the act allowed the trial of an Englishman in Scotland if the felony was committed there, and he was later arrested in England; it became effective after a similar act had been passed in Scotland.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge50britgoog#page/n248/mode/2up Statutes at Large - Volume 7 - 39 Elizabeth to 12 Charles II - 1597-8 to 1660], p.216]</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Restoration (England)|Restoration]] and long-running lawlessness by [[Moss-trooper|Moss troopers]] nearly six decades later, parliament passed the Moss Troopers Act 1662 (13 & 14 Cha. 2. c. 22) for the border area; it was [[long title]]d ''An Act for preventing of Theft and Rapine upon the Northern Borders of England.'' Section seven of the act revives both previous acts passed under James I.<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/statutes-realm/vol5/pp417-418 Statutes of the Realm: Volume 5, 1628-80], p.417</ref> With the 1662 act about to expire, the sixth session of [[Cavalier Parliament]] passed the Moss Troopers Act 1666 (18 Cha. 2 c. 3), long titled ''An Act to continue a former Act for preventing of Thefte and Rapine upon the Northerne Borders of England.'' Under section two of the act, the [[benefit of clergy]] was taken away from those convicted (generally meaning a death sentence), or otherwise, the notorious thieves and spoil-takers in Northumberland or Cumberland were to be [[penal transportation|transported]] to America, \"there to remaine and not to returne\".<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/statutes-realm/vol5/p598 Statutes of the Realm: Volume 5, 1628-80], p.598</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge20unkngoog#page/n587/mode/2up Statutes at Large, Volume 24, Index for acts passed before 1 Geo. 3] p.&nbsp;581</ref>\n\nGenerally associated with several historic events of the period, as well as continuing lawlessness, or the consideration of insufficient government control to prevent \"theft and rapine upon the northern borders of England\", these acts were repeatedly continued over the next 80 years. The initial acts include the Moss Trooper Acts of 1677 (29 & 30 Cha. 2 c. 2),<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge29britgoog#page/n447/mode/2up \"An act for continuance of two former acts for preventing theft and rapine upon the northern borders of England\"]</ref> 1685 (1 Jas. 2 c.  14),<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge29britgoog#page/n485/mode/2up \"An act for the continuance of three former acts for preventing of theft and rapine upon the northern borders of England\"]</ref> 1695 (7 & 8 Will. 3 c.  17),<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge38britgoog#page/n441/mode/2up \"An act for the continuing four former acts for preventing theft and rapine on the northern borders of England\"]</ref> 1700 (12 & 13 Will. 3 c. 6),<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge31britgoog#page/n411/mode/2up \"An act for continuing the acts therein mentioned for preventing theft and rapine on the northern borders of England\"]</ref> and 1712 (12 Ann. c. 10).<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge69britgoog#page/n58/mode/2up \"An act for continuing the acts therein mentioned, for preventing theft and rapine upon the northern borders of England\"]</ref> Starting in 1732, although the 'Moss trooper' [[short title]] was dropped, the enforcement acts were continued by other variously named acts, most of which continued the established descriptive phrase \"for preventing theft and rapine upon the northern borders of England\", as the first item included.  These later acts include the Perpetuation of Various Laws Act 1732 (6 Geo. 2 c.  37),<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge03britgoog#page/n484/mode/2up \u201cAn act ... and for continuing an act made in the thirteenth and fourteenth years of the reign of King Charles the Second, for preventing theft and rapine on the northern borders of England; and for reviving and continuing certain clauses in two other acts made for the same purpose\"]</ref> the Universities (Wine Licences) Act 1743 (17 Geo. 2 c. 40),<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge01britgoog#page/n318/mode/2up \"An act to continue the several laws therein mentioned for preventing theft and rapine on the northern borders of England; ...\"]</ref> and the Continuance of Acts, 1750 (24 Geo. 2 c. 57),<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge67britgoog#page/n342/mode/2up \"An act to continue the several laws therein mentioned; for preventing theft and rapine on the northern borders of England; ...\"]</ref> which continued previous acts until 1 September 1757 \"and from thence to the end of the then next session of parliament\".\n\n==Border surnames and clan status==\n[[File:Hermitage Castle 06.jpg|thumb|left|[[Hermitage Castle]], the strength of [[Liddesdale]] and an important stronghold for the Scottish Marches. Its holder, the Keeper of Liddesdale, usually had equal status to the Scottish Wardens of the Marches.]]\nThe Border families can be referred to as clans, as the [[Scot]]s themselves appear to have used both terms interchangeably until the 19th century. In an Act of the [[Scottish Parliament]] of 1587 there is the description of the \"Chiftanis and chieffis of all clannis ... duelland in the hielands or bordouris\" \u2013 thus using the word clan and chief to describe both Highland and Lowland families. The act goes on to list the various Border clans. Later, Sir George MacKenzie of Rosehaugh, the Lord Advocate (Attorney General) writing in 1680 said \"By the term 'chief' we call the representative of the family from the word chef or head and in the [[Irish language|Irish]] (Gaelic) with us the chief of the family is called the head of the clan\". Thus, the words chief or head, and clan or family, are interchangeable. It is therefore possible to talk of the [[MacDonald]] family or the Maxwell clan. The idea that Highlanders should be listed as clans while the Lowlanders are listed as families originated as a 19th-century convention.<ref>[http://www.electricscotland.com/webclans/clans_families_septs.htm Clans, Families and Septs<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOther terms were also used to describe the Border families, such as the \"Riding Surnames\" and the \"Graynes\" thereof. This can be equated to the system of the Highland Clans and their [[Sept (social)|sept]]s. e.g. [[Clan Donald]] and [[Clan MacDonald of Sleat]], can be compared with the [[Duke of Buccleuch|Scotts of Buccleuch]] and the Scotts of Harden and elsewhere. Both Border Graynes and Highland septs however, had the essential feature of patriarchal leadership by the chief of the name, and had territories in which most of their kindred lived. Border families did practice customs similar to those of the [[Gaels]], such as tutorship when an heir who was a minor succeeded to the chiefship, and giving bonds of [[manrent]]. Although feudalism existed, loyalty to kin was much more important and this is what distinguished the Borderers from other lowland Scots.{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}}\n\n===Marches===\n\nIn 1587 the [[Parliament of Scotland]] passed a statute: \"For the quieting and keping in obiedince of the disorderit subjectis inhabitantis of the borders hielands and Ilis.\"<ref>Great Britain III Acts of the Parliament of Scotland pp.466\u2013467 (1587)</ref> Attached to the statute was a Roll of surnames from both the Borders and Highlands. The Borders portion listed 17 'clannis' with a Chief and their associated Marches:\n[[File:Marches_map.JPG|right|thumb|Regions of the Scottish marches]]\n'''''Middle March'''''\n*[[Clan Elliot|Elliot]], [[Clan Armstrong|Armstrong]], Nixon, Crozier\n'''''West March'''''\n*Scott, Bates, Little, [[Thomson (surname)|Thomson]], Glendenning, Irvine, Bell, [[Clan Carruthers|Carruthers]], [[Graham (surname)|Graham]], [[Clan Johnstone|Johnstone]], Jardine, Moffat and Latimer.\n\nOf the Border Clans or Graynes listed on this roll, [[Clan Elliot|Elliot]], [[Clan Carruthers|Carruthers]], [[Clan Scott|Scott]], [[Clan Irvine|Irvine]], [[Clan Graham|Graham]], [[Clan Johnstone|Johnstone]], [[Clan Jardine|Jardine]] and [[Clan Moffat|Moffat]] are registered with the Court of Lord Lyon in Edinburgh as Scottish Clans (with a Chief), others such as [[Clan Armstrong|Armstrong]], [[Clan Little|Little]] and Bell are [[armigerous]] clans with no Chief, while such as [[Clan Blackadder]], also an [[armigerous]] clan in the Middle Ages, later died out or lost their lands, and are unregistered with the Lyon Court.\n\nThe historic riding surnames recorded by George MacDonald Fraser in ''The Steel Bonnets'' (1989)<ref>George McDonald Fraser, pp.&nbsp;56\u201365</ref> are:\n\n'''''East March'''''\n* Scotland: [[Clan Home|Hume]], [[Clan Trotter|Trotter]], [[Dixon Baronets|Dixon]], [[Bromfield (surname)|Bromfield]], [[Craw (surname)|Craw]], [[Clan Cranstoun|Cranston]].\n* England: [[Forster (surname)|Forster]], [[Selby family|Selby]], [[Gray (surname)|Gray]], [[Dunn (surname)|Dunn]].\n'''''Middle March'''''\n* Scotland: Burns, [[Clan Kerr|Kerr]], [[Clan Young|Young]], [[Clan Pringle|Pringle]], Davison, Gilchrist, [[Tait (surname)|Tait]] of East Teviotdale. [[Clan Scott|Scott]], Oliver, [[Clan Turnbull|Turnbull]], Rutherford of West Teviotdale. [[Clan Armstrong|Armstrong]], Croser, [[Clan Eliott|Elliot]], Nixon, [[Clan Douglas|Douglas]], Laidlaw, [[Routledge]], Turner, [[Clan Henderson|Henderson]] of Liddesdale.\n* England: Anderson, Potts, [[Reed (name)|Reed]], [[Clan Hall|Hall]], Hedley of Redesdale. Charlton, Robson, Dodd, Dodds, Milburn, Yarrow, [[Stapleton (surname)|Stapleton]] of Tynedale. Also Fenwick, [[Ogle family|Ogle]], Heron, Witherington, Medford (later [[Mitford family|Mitford]]), Collingwood, Carnaby, Shaftoe, Ridley, Stokoe, Stamper, Wilkinson, Hunter, [[Thomson (surname)|Thomson]], Jamieson.\n'''''West March'''''\n* Scotland: Bell, [[Clan Irvine|Irvine]], [[Clan Johnstone|Johnstone]], [[Clan Maxwell|Maxwell]], Carlisle, Beattie, [[Clan Little|Little]], [[Clan Carruthers|Carruthers]], Glendenning, Routledge, [[Clan Moffat|Moffat]].\n* England: Graham, [[Hetherington]], Musgrave, Storey, Lowther, Curwen, [[Salkeld]], Dacre, Harden, [[Hodgson]], Routledge, Tailor, Noble.\n\nRelationships between the Border clans varied from uneasy alliance to open, deadly [[feud]]. It took little to start a feud; a chance quarrel or misuse of office was sufficient. Feuds might continue for years until patched up in the face of invasion from the other kingdoms or when the outbreak of other feuds caused alliances to shift. The border was easily destabilised if Graynes from opposite sides of the border were at feud. Feuds also provided ready excuse for particularly murderous raids or pursuits.\n\nRiders did not wear identifying [[tartan]]s. The tradition of family tartans dates from the [[Victorian era|Victorian]] era and was inspired by the novels of [[Sir Walter Scott]]. The typical dress of reivers included [[trews]], [[Jack of plate]], steel bonnets ([[helmet]]s), and [[riding boot]]s.\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Crossing the Tweed on Braw Lad's Day, Galashiels.jpg|thumb|310px|left|Skills of horsemanship are kept alive in the Borders: fording the [[River Tweed]] on Braw Lad's Day, [[Galashiels]] 2011]]\n[[File:Galashiels Reiver Statue 02.JPG|thumb|250px|left|Reiver statue at Galashiels]]\nLong after they were gone, the reivers were romanticised by writers such as [[Sir Walter Scott]] (''[[Minstrelsy of the Scottish Border]]''), although he made mistakes; the term [[Moss-trooper]], which he used, refers to one of the robbers that existed after the real Reivers had been put down. Nevertheless, Scott was a native of the borders, writing down histories which had been passed on in folk tradition or ballad. The stories of legendary border reivers like [[Kinmont Willie Armstrong]] were often retold in folk-song as Border ballads. There are also local legends, such as the \"Dish of Spurs\" which would be served to a border chieftain of the Charltons to remind him that the larder was empty and it was time to acquire more plunder. Scottish author [[Nigel Tranter]] revisited these themes in his historical and contemporary novels.  Scottish Border poet, and Australian bush balladeer, [[William Henry Ogilvie|Will H. Ogilvie]] (1869\u20131963) wrote several poems about the reivers, including ''The reiver's heart'' (1903), ''The raiders'' (1904), ''Whaup o' the rede: a ballad of the border raiders'' (1909), ''[[Kirkhope Tower]]'' (1913), and ''Ho! for the blades of Harden''.\n\nThe names of the [[Reiver]] families are still very much apparent amongst the inhabitants of the [[Scottish Borders]], Northumberland and [[Cumbria]] today. Reiving families (particularly those large or brutal enough to carry significant influence) have left the local population passionate about their territory on both sides of the Border. Newspapers have described the local cross-border rugby fixtures as 'annual re-runs of the bloody [[Battle of Otterburn]]'.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} Despite this there has been much cross-border migration since the Pacification of the Borders, and families that were once Scots now identify themselves as English and vice versa.\n\n[[Hawick]] in Scotland holds an annual Reivers' festival as do the Schomberg Society in Kilkeel, Northern Ireland (the two often co-operate). The summer festival in the Borders town of [[Duns]] is headed by the \"Reiver\" and \"Reiver's Lass\", a young man and young woman elected from the inhabitants of the town and surrounding area. The Ulster-Scots Agency's first two leaflets from the 'Scots Legacy' series feature the story of the historic Ulster tartan and the origins of the kilt and the Border Reivers.\n\nBorderers (particularly those banished by [[James VI of Scotland]]) took part in the [[plantation of Ulster]] becoming the people known as [[Ulster-Scots]] ([[Scotch-Irish American|Scotch-Irish]] in America). Reiver descendants can be found throughout Ulster with names such as Elliot, Armstrong, Beattie, Bell, Carruthers, Hume and Heron, Rutledge, and Turnbulls amongst others.\n\nBorder surnames can also be found throughout the major areas of [[Scots-Irish American|Scotch-Irish]] settlement in the United States, and particularly in the [[Appalachian Mountains|Appalachian]] region. The historian [[David Hackett Fischer]] (1989) has shown in detail how the Anglo-Scottish border culture became rooted in parts of the United States, especially the [[Upland South]]. Author [[George MacDonald Fraser]] wryly observed or imagined Border traits and names among controversial people in modern American history: Presidents [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] and [[Richard Nixon]], among others. It is also noted that, in 1969, a descendant of the Borderers, [[Neil Armstrong]], was the first person to set foot on the moon. In 1972 Armstrong was made a [[Freedom of the city|freeman]] of the town of [[Langholm]] in Scotland, the home of his ancestors.\n\nThe artist [[Gordon Young (artist)|Gordon Young]] created a public art work in Carlisle: ''Cursing Stone and Reiver Pavement'', a nod to [[Gavin Dunbar (archbishop of Glasgow)|Gavin Dunbar]], the Archbishop of Glasgow's 1525 ''Monition of Cursing''.  Names of Reiver families are set into the paving of a walkway which connects [[Tullie House Museum]] to [[Carlisle Castle]] under a main road, and part of the bishop's curse is displayed on a 14-ton granite boulder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gordonyoung.net/carlise_cursingstone.html|title=Cursing Stone & Reiver Pavement / Carlisle, 2001|publisher=Gordon Young|accessdate=23 November 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227133140/http://gordonyoung.net/carlise_cursingstone.html|archivedate=27 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Debatable Lands]]\n* [[History of Northumberland]]\n* ''[[The Borderers]]'' (Television series)\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|last=Carey|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Carey, 1st Earl of Monmouth|title=The Stirring World of Robert Carey, Robert Carey's Memoirs 1577\u20131625|publisher=RippingYarns.com|isbn=1-904466-29-X}}\n* {{cite book|last=Durham|first=Keith|author2=McBride, Angus|title=The Border Reivers: The story of the Anglo-Scottish borderlands|year=1995|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=1-85532-417-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781855324176}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ennis|first=Garth|title=War Stories: Volume 2|year=2006|publisher=Vertigo|isbn=1-4012-1039-2}}\n* {{cite book|last=Fischer|first=David Hackett|authorlink=David Hackett Fischer|title=[[Albion's Seed: Four British Folkways in America]]|year=1989|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford and New York}}\n* {{cite book|last=Howker|first=Janni|authorlink=Janni Howker|title=Martin Farrell|year=1997|publisher=Red Fox|isbn=978-0-09-918161-3}}\n* {{cite book|last=MacDonald Fraser|first=George|authorlink=George MacDonald Fraser|title=The Steel Bonnets|year=1971|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=0-00-272746-3}}\n* {{cite book|last=Moffat|first=Alistair|title=The Reivers|year=2008|publisher=Birlinn|location=Edinburgh|isbn=978-1-84158-674-8}}\n* {{cite book|last=Turnbull|first=Rob|title=The Border Reivers: A stain on the image of Tudor England|publisher=[[Medieval History Magazine]]|volume=4|date=December 2003}}\n* {{cite book|last=Moss|first=Tom|title=Deadlock and Deliverance: The Capture and Rescue of Kinmont Willie Armstrong|year=2007|publisher=Rose Cottage Publications|isbn=978-0-9558016-0-0}}\n* {{cite book|last=Tait|first=Jon|title=Dick the Devil's Bairns: Breaking the Border Mafia|year=2018|publisher=Tredition|isbn=978-3-7482-2361-0}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.borderreivers.co.uk The Border Reivers Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090126155155/http://nwlink.com/~scotlass/border.htm The Border Reivers]\n* [http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~gallgaedhil/ Border Reivers DNA Project]\n* [http://the-border-reivers.co.uk Yet Another Border Reivers Website]\n* [http://www.everymansprey.com The Routledge Reivers]\n* [http://www.reivershistory.co.uk The Capture and Rescue of Kinmont Willie Armstrong]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304074111/http://www.go-britain.com/html/borders_map.htm#borders Borders Map with surnames]\n\n{{Scottish clans}}\n\n[[Category:Anglo-Scottish border]]\n[[Category:History of Europe]]\n[[Category:Border Reivers| ]]\n[[Category:Cavalry]]\n[[Category:History of Cumberland]]\n[[Category:History of Cumbria]]\n[[Category:History of Northumberland]]\n[[Category:Military history of Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Military history of Northumberland]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Scottish Borders]]\n[[Category:History of the Scottish Borders]]\n[[Category:Tudor England]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{redirect|Reivers|the actor|David Reivers|articles with similar names|The Reivers (disambiguation)}}\n{{engvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n[[File:Reivers raid on Gilnockie Tower.jpg|thumb|Reivers at [[Gilnockie Tower]], from a 19th-century print|alt=|366x366px]]\n[[File:Wat o' Harden's horn.JPG|thumb|273x273px|Notorious raider, [[Walter Scott of Harden]]'s horn, noted in a poem called the \"The Reiver's Wedding\" by [[Walter Scott|Sir Walter Scott]]:\n\n\n\"He took a bugle frae his side,\n\nWith names carved o'er and o'er,\n\nFull many a chief of meikle pride,\n\nThat Border bugle bore.\"\n\n\n(A fragment of the full poem.)]]\n'''Border reivers''' were [[Cattle raiding|raiders]] along the [[Anglo-Scottish border]] from the late 13th century to the beginning of the 17th century. Their ranks consisted of both [[Scotland|Scottish]] and [[England|English]] people, and they raided the entire [[Border country]] without regard to their victims' nationality. Their heyday was in the last hundred years of their existence, during the time of the [[House of Stuart]] in the [[Kingdom of Scotland]] and the [[House of Tudor]] in the [[Kingdom of England]]\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Dryhope Tower - geograph.org.uk - 195093.jpg|thumb|278x278px|[[Dryhope Tower]] built in the 1500s for protection against the reivers]]\nScotland and England were frequently at war during the late [[Middle Ages]]. During these wars, the livelihood of the people on the Borders was devastated by the contending armies. Even when the countries were not formally at war, tension remained high, and royal authority in either or both kingdoms was often weak, particularly in remote locations. The difficulty and uncertainties of basic human survival meant that communities and/or people kindred to each other would seek security through group strength and cunning. They would attempt to improve their livelihoods at their nominal enemies' expense, enemies who were frequently also just trying to survive. Loyalty to a feeble or distant monarch and reliance on the effectiveness of the law usually made people a target for [[Raid (military)|depredations]] rather than conferring any security.\n\nThere were other factors which promoted a [[Predation|predatory]] mode of living in the Borders. A system of inheritance called [[gavelkind]] meant that estates, and particularly land, were divided equally between all sons on a man's death; although this was considered more fair than [[primogeniture]], it also meant that many people owned insufficient land to survive.<ref name=Durham5>Durham & McBride, p.5</ref> Also, much of the border region is mountainous or open moorland, unsuitable for arable farming but good for grazing. Livestock was easily rustled and driven back to raiders' territory by mounted reivers who knew the country well. The raiders also often removed easily portable household goods or valuables, and took prisoners for ransom.\n\nThe attitudes of the English and Scottish governments towards the border families alternated from indulgence and even encouragement, as these fierce families served as the first line of defence against invasion across the border, to draconian and indiscriminate punishment when their lawlessness became intolerable to the authorities.\n\n''Reive'', a noun meaning raid, comes from the Middle English (Scots) ''reifen.'' The verb ''reave'' meaning \"plunder, rob\", a closely related word, comes from the Middle English ''reven''. There also exists a [[Northumbrian English|Northumbrian]] and [[Scots language|Scots]] verb ''reifen.''  All three derive from [[Old English]] ''r\u0113afian'' which means \"to rob, plunder, pillage\".<ref>[http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/Reiver merriam-webster.com]</ref> The corresponding verb in Dutch is \"(be)roven\", and \"(be)rauben\" in German.\n\n==Nature==\n[[File:WatHarden.jpg|thumb|right|''[[Walter Scott of Harden|Auld Wat of Harden]]'' by [[Tom Scott (painter)|Tom Scott]]. A romanticised image of a notorious raider, Walter Scott of Harden.]]\nThe reivers were both English and Scottish and raided both sides of the border impartially, so long as the people they raided had no powerful protectors and no connection to their own kin. Their activities, although usually within a day's ride of the border, extended both north and south of their main haunts. English raiders were reported to have hit the outskirts of [[Edinburgh]], and Scottish raids were known as far south as [[Yorkshire]]. The largest of these was [[The Great Raid of 1322]], during the [[Scottish Wars of Independence]], where it reached as far south as [[Chorley]]. The main raiding season ran through the early winter months, when the nights were longest and the cattle and horses fat from having spent the summer grazing. The numbers involved in a raid might range from a few dozen to organised campaigns involving up to three thousand riders.<ref>George MacDonald Fraser, p.38</ref>\n\nWhen raiding, or riding, as it was termed, the reivers rode light on hardy nags or ponies renowned for the ability to pick their way over the boggy moss lands (see: [[Galloway pony]], [[Hobelar]]). The original dress of a [[Northumbrian tartan|shepherd's plaid]] was later replaced by light armour such as [[brigandine]]s or [[Jack of plate|jacks of plate]] (a type of sleeveless [[doublet (clothing)|doublet]] into which small plates of steel were stitched), and metal helmets such as [[burgonet]]s or [[Morion (helmet)|morions]]; hence their nickname of the \"steel bonnets\". They were armed with light lances and small shields, and sometimes also with [[longbow]]s, or light [[crossbow]]s, known as \"latches\", or later on in their history with one or more pistols. They invariably also carried [[sword]]s and [[dirk]]s.\n\n==Borderers as soldiers==\nBorder reivers were sometimes in demand as [[mercenaries|mercenary soldiers]], owing to their recognized skills as light [[cavalry]].  Reivers sometimes served in English or Scottish armies in the [[Low Countries]] and in Ireland, often to avoid having harsher penalties enacted upon themselves and their families. Reivers fighting as levied soldiers played important roles in the battles at [[Battle of Flodden|Flodden]] and [[Battle of Solway Moss|Solway Moss]]. After meeting one reiver (the [[Walter Scott, 1st Lord Scott of Buccleuch|''Bold Buccleugh'']]), [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth I]] is quoted as having said that \"with ten thousand such men, [[James VI and I|James VI]] could shake any throne in Europe.\" \n\nThese borderers proved difficult to control, however, within larger national armies. They were already in the habit of claiming any nationality or none, depending on who was asking and where they perceived the individual advantage to be. Many had relatives on both sides of Scottish-English conflicts despite prevailing laws against international marriage. They could be badly-behaved in camp, seeing fellow soldiers as sources of plunder. As warriors more loyal to clans than to nations, their commitment to the work was always in doubt. At battles such as [[Battle of Ancrum Moor|Ancrum Moor]] in Scotland in 1545, borderers changed sides in mid-combat to curry favour with the likely victors. At the [[Battle of Pinkie Cleugh]] in 1547, an observer ([[William Patten (historian)|William Patten]]) noticed Scottish and English borderers chatting with each other, then putting on a spirited show of combat once they knew they had been spotted.<ref>Moffat</ref>\n\n==Dwellings and fortifications==\n[[File:Black Middens Bastle - geograph.org.uk - 1224658.jpg|left|thumb|[[Black Middens Bastle House]], a surviving bastle house near [[Kielder Water]] in Northumberland]]\n\nThe inhabitants of the Borders had to live in a state of constant alert, and for self-protection, they built fortified [[Tower houses in Britain and Ireland|tower house]]s.\n\nIn the very worst periods of warfare, people were unable to construct more than crude turf cabins, the destruction of which would be little loss. When times allowed however, they built houses designed as much for defence as shelter. The [[bastle house]] was a stout two-storeyed building. The lower floor was used to keep the most valuable livestock and horses. The upper storey housed the people, and often could be reached only by an external ladder which was pulled up at night or if danger threatened. The stone walls were up to {{convert|3|ft|m|1}} thick, and the roof was of slate or stone tiles. Only narrow arrow slits provided light and ventilation.<ref>Durham & McBride, p.24</ref> Such dwellings could not be set on fire, and while they could be captured, for example by smoking out the defenders with fires of damp straw or using scaling ladders to reach the roof, they were usually not worth the time and effort.\n\n[[Peel tower]]s (also spelled pele towers) were usually three-storeyed buildings, constructed specifically for defensive purposes by the authorities, or for prestigious individuals such as the heads of clans. [[Smailholm Tower]] is one of many surviving peel towers. Like bastle houses, they were very strongly constructed for defence. If necessary, they could be temporarily abandoned and stuffed full of smouldering turf to prevent an enemy (such as a government army) destroying them with gunpowder.<ref>Durham & McBride, p.23</ref>\n\nPeel towers and bastle houses were often surrounded by a stone wall known as a barmkin, inside which cattle and other livestock were kept overnight.\n\n==Law and order==\n[[File:Late-medieval jack, National Museum of Scotland collection.jpg|thumb|A leather jack of the kind worn by reivers in the 16th century]]\nDuring periods of nominal peace, a special body of [[customary law]], known as [[March law (Anglo-Scottish border)|March law]] or Border law, grew up to deal with the situation. Under border law, a person who had been raided had the right to mount a counter-raid within six days, even across the border, to recover his goods. This \"hot trod\" had to proceed with \"hound and horne, hew and cry\",<ref>Durham & McBride, p. 20.</ref> making a racket and carrying a piece of burning turf on a spear point to openly announce their purpose, to distinguish themselves from unlawful raiders proceeding covertly. They might use a [[sleuth hound]] (also known as a \"slew dogge\") to follow raiders' tracks. These dogs were valuable, and part of the established forces (on the English side of the border, at least).<ref>George MacDonald Fraser, pp. 95\u201396</ref> Any person meeting this counter-raid was required to ride along and offer such help as he could, on pain of being considered complicit with the raiders. The \"cold trod\" mounted after six days required official sanction. Officers such as the Deputy Warden of the English West March had the specific duty of \"following the trod\".<ref>George MacDonald Fraser, p. 215 fn.</ref>\n\nBoth sides of the border were divided into [[Scottish Marches|Marches]], each under a [[Lord Warden of the Marches|march warden]]. The march wardens' various duties included the maintenance of patrols, watches and garrisons to deter raiding from the other kingdom. On occasion, march wardens could make ''warden roades'' to recover loot, and to make a point to raiders and officials.\n\nThe march wardens also had the duty of maintaining such justice and equity as was possible. The respective kingdoms' march wardens would meet at appointed times along the border itself to settle claims against people on their side of the border by people from the other kingdom. These occasions, known as \"Days of Truce\", were much like fairs, with entertainment and much socialising. For reivers it was an opportunity to meet (lawfully) with relatives or friends normally separated by the border. It was not unknown for violence to break out even at such truce days.\n\nMarch wardens (and the lesser officers such as keepers of fortified places) were rarely effective at maintaining the law. The Scottish wardens were usually borderers themselves, and were complicit in raiding. They almost invariably showed favour to their own kindred, which caused jealousy and even hatred among other Scottish border families. Many English officers were from southern counties in England and often could not command the loyalty or respect of their locally recruited subordinates or the local population. Local officers such as [[Sir John Forster]], who was Warden of the Middle March for almost 35 years, became quite as well known for venality as his most notorious Scottish counterparts.<ref>George MacDonald Fraser, pp.139\u2013140</ref>\n\nBy the death of [[Elizabeth I of England]], things had come to such a pitch along the border that the English government considered re-fortifying and rebuilding [[Hadrian's Wall]].<ref>George MacDonald Fraser, p.210</ref> When Elizabeth died, there was an especially violent outbreak of raiding known as \"Ill Week\", resulting from the convenient belief that the laws of a kingdom were suspended between the death of a sovereign and the proclamation of the successor.<ref>George MacDonald Fraser, p.360</ref> Upon his accession to the English throne, [[James I of England|James VI]] of Scotland (who became James I of England) moved hard against the reivers, abolishing border law and the very term \"Borders\" in favour of \"Middle [[Shire]]s,\" and dealing out stern justice to reivers.\n\n===Legislation===\nIn 1606 an act (4 Jas. 1. c. 1) to assist the recent [[Union of the Crowns]] was enacted; it was [[long title]]d ''An act for the utter abolition of all memory of hostility, and the dependence thereof, between England and Scotland, and for repressing of occasions of disorders, and disorders in time to come''. The act repealed nine English laws enacted over the previous centuries and considered hostile to Scotland; the repeal became effective when 13 Scottish laws considered hostile to England had been repealed.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge50britgoog#page/n226/mode/2up Statutes at Large - Volume 7 - 39 Elizabeth to 12 Charles II - 1597-8 to 1660], p.195</ref> Three years later an act (7 Jas. 1 c. 1) dealing with criminal law in the border region was enacted; it was long titled ''An act for the better execution of justice, and suppressing of criminal offenders, in the north parts of the kingdom of England.'' To deal with cross-border flight, the act allowed the trial of an Englishman in Scotland if the felony was committed there, and he was later arrested in England; it became effective after a similar act had been passed in Scotland.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge50britgoog#page/n248/mode/2up Statutes at Large - Volume 7 - 39 Elizabeth to 12 Charles II - 1597-8 to 1660], p.216]</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Restoration (England)|Restoration]] and long-running lawlessness by [[Moss-trooper|Moss troopers]] nearly six decades later, parliament passed the Moss Troopers Act 1662 (13 & 14 Cha. 2. c. 22) for the border area; it was [[long title]]d ''An Act for preventing of Theft and Rapine upon the Northern Borders of England.'' Section seven of the act revives both previous acts passed under James I.<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/statutes-realm/vol5/pp417-418 Statutes of the Realm: Volume 5, 1628-80], p.417</ref> With the 1662 act about to expire, the sixth session of [[Cavalier Parliament]] passed the Moss Troopers Act 1666 (18 Cha. 2 c. 3), long titled ''An Act to continue a former Act for preventing of Thefte and Rapine upon the Northerne Borders of England.'' Under section two of the act, the [[benefit of clergy]] was taken away from those convicted (generally meaning a death sentence), or otherwise, the notorious thieves and spoil-takers in Northumberland or Cumberland were to be [[penal transportation|transported]] to America, \"there to remaine and not to returne\".<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/statutes-realm/vol5/p598 Statutes of the Realm: Volume 5, 1628-80], p.598</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge20unkngoog#page/n587/mode/2up Statutes at Large, Volume 24, Index for acts passed before 1 Geo. 3] p.&nbsp;581</ref>\n\nGenerally associated with several historic events of the period, as well as continuing lawlessness, or the consideration of insufficient government control to prevent \"theft and rapine upon the northern borders of England\", these acts were repeatedly continued over the next 80 years. The initial acts include the Moss Trooper Acts of 1677 (29 & 30 Cha. 2 c. 2),<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge29britgoog#page/n447/mode/2up \"An act for continuance of two former acts for preventing theft and rapine upon the northern borders of England\"]</ref> 1685 (1 Jas. 2 c.  14),<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge29britgoog#page/n485/mode/2up \"An act for the continuance of three former acts for preventing of theft and rapine upon the northern borders of England\"]</ref> 1695 (7 & 8 Will. 3 c.  17),<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge38britgoog#page/n441/mode/2up \"An act for the continuing four former acts for preventing theft and rapine on the northern borders of England\"]</ref> 1700 (12 & 13 Will. 3 c. 6),<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge31britgoog#page/n411/mode/2up \"An act for continuing the acts therein mentioned for preventing theft and rapine on the northern borders of England\"]</ref> and 1712 (12 Ann. c. 10).<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge69britgoog#page/n58/mode/2up \"An act for continuing the acts therein mentioned, for preventing theft and rapine upon the northern borders of England\"]</ref> Starting in 1732, although the 'Moss trooper' [[short title]] was dropped, the enforcement acts were continued by other variously named acts, most of which continued the established descriptive phrase \"for preventing theft and rapine upon the northern borders of England\", as the first item included.  These later acts include the Perpetuation of Various Laws Act 1732 (6 Geo. 2 c.  37),<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge03britgoog#page/n484/mode/2up \u201cAn act ... and for continuing an act made in the thirteenth and fourteenth years of the reign of King Charles the Second, for preventing theft and rapine on the northern borders of England; and for reviving and continuing certain clauses in two other acts made for the same purpose\"]</ref> the Universities (Wine Licences) Act 1743 (17 Geo. 2 c. 40),<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge01britgoog#page/n318/mode/2up \"An act to continue the several laws therein mentioned for preventing theft and rapine on the northern borders of England; ...\"]</ref> and the Continuance of Acts, 1750 (24 Geo. 2 c. 57),<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statutesatlarge67britgoog#page/n342/mode/2up \"An act to continue the several laws therein mentioned; for preventing theft and rapine on the northern borders of England; ...\"]</ref> which continued previous acts until 1 September 1757 \"and from thence to the end of the then next session of parliament\".\n\n==Border surnames and clan status==\n[[File:Hermitage Castle 06.jpg|thumb|left|[[Hermitage Castle]], the strength of [[Liddesdale]] and an important stronghold for the Scottish Marches. Its holder, the Keeper of Liddesdale, usually had equal status to the Scottish Wardens of the Marches.]]\nThe Border families can be referred to as clans, as the [[Scot]]s themselves appear to have used both terms interchangeably until the 19th century. In an Act of the [[Scottish Parliament]] of 1587 there is the description of the \"Chiftanis and chieffis of all clannis ... duelland in the hielands or bordouris\" \u2013 thus using the word clan and chief to describe both Highland and Lowland families. The act goes on to list the various Border clans. Later, Sir George MacKenzie of Rosehaugh, the Lord Advocate (Attorney General) writing in 1680 said \"By the term 'chief' we call the representative of the family from the word chef or head and in the [[Irish language|Irish]] (Gaelic) with us the chief of the family is called the head of the clan\". Thus, the words chief or head, and clan or family, are interchangeable. It is therefore possible to talk of the [[MacDonald]] family or the Maxwell clan. The idea that Highlanders should be listed as clans while the Lowlanders are listed as families originated as a 19th-century convention.<ref>[http://www.electricscotland.com/webclans/clans_families_septs.htm Clans, Families and Septs<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOther terms were also used to describe the Border families, such as the \"Riding Surnames\" and the \"Graynes\" thereof. This can be equated to the system of the Highland Clans and their [[Sept (social)|sept]]s. e.g. [[Clan Donald]] and [[Clan MacDonald of Sleat]], can be compared with the [[Duke of Buccleuch|Scotts of Buccleuch]] and the Scotts of Harden and elsewhere. Both Border Graynes and Highland septs however, had the essential feature of patriarchal leadership by the chief of the name, and had territories in which most of their kindred lived. Border families did practice customs similar to those of the [[Gaels]], such as tutorship when an heir who was a minor succeeded to the chiefship, and giving bonds of [[manrent]]. Although feudalism existed, loyalty to kin was much more important and this is what distinguished the Borderers from other lowland Scots.{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}}\n\n===Marches===\n\nIn 1587 the [[Parliament of Scotland]] passed a statute: \"For the quieting and keping in obiedince of the disorderit subjectis inhabitantis of the borders hielands and Ilis.\"<ref>Great Britain III Acts of the Parliament of Scotland pp.466\u2013467 (1587)</ref> Attached to the statute was a Roll of surnames from both the Borders and Highlands. The Borders portion listed 17 'clannis' with a Chief and their associated Marches:\n[[File:Marches_map.JPG|right|thumb|Regions of the Scottish marches]]\n'''''Middle March'''''\n*[[Clan Elliot|Elliot]], [[Clan Armstrong|Armstrong]], Nixon, Crozier\n'''''West March'''''\n*Scott, Bates, Little, [[Thomson (surname)|Thomson]], Glendenning, Irvine, Bell, [[Clan Carruthers|Carruthers]], [[Graham (surname)|Graham]], [[Clan Johnstone|Johnstone]], Jardine, Moffat and Latimer.\n\nOf the Border Clans or Graynes listed on this roll, [[Clan Elliot|Elliot]], [[Clan Carruthers|Carruthers]], [[Clan Scott|Scott]], [[Clan Irvine|Irvine]], [[Clan Graham|Graham]], [[Clan Johnstone|Johnstone]], [[Clan Jardine|Jardine]] and [[Clan Moffat|Moffat]] are registered with the Court of Lord Lyon in Edinburgh as Scottish Clans (with a Chief), others such as [[Clan Armstrong|Armstrong]], [[Clan Little|Little]] and Bell are [[armigerous]] clans with no Chief, while such as [[Clan Blackadder]], also an [[armigerous]] clan in the Middle Ages, later died out or lost their lands, and are unregistered with the Lyon Court.\n\nThe historic riding surnames recorded by George MacDonald Fraser in ''The Steel Bonnets'' (1989)<ref>George McDonald Fraser, pp.&nbsp;56\u201365</ref> are:\n\n'''''East March'''''\n* Scotland: [[Clan Home|Hume]], [[Clan Trotter|Trotter]], [[Dixon Baronets|Dixon]], [[Bromfield (surname)|Bromfield]], [[Craw (surname)|Craw]], [[Clan Cranstoun|Cranston]].\n* England: [[Forster (surname)|Forster]], [[Selby family|Selby]], [[Gray (surname)|Gray]], [[Dunn (surname)|Dunn]].\n'''''Middle March'''''\n* Scotland: Burns, [[Clan Kerr|Kerr]], [[Clan Young|Young]], [[Clan Pringle|Pringle]], Davison, Gilchrist, [[Tait (surname)|Tait]] of East Teviotdale. [[Clan Scott|Scott]], Oliver, [[Clan Turnbull|Turnbull]], Rutherford of West Teviotdale. [[Clan Armstrong|Armstrong]], Croser, [[Clan Eliott|Elliot]], Nixon, [[Clan Douglas|Douglas]], Laidlaw, [[Routledge]], Turner, [[Clan Henderson|Henderson]] of Liddesdale.\n* England: Anderson, Potts, [[Reed (name)|Reed]], [[Clan Hall|Hall]], Hedley of Redesdale. Charlton, Robson, Dodd, Dodds, Milburn, Yarrow, [[Stapleton (surname)|Stapleton]] of Tynedale. Also Fenwick, [[Ogle family|Ogle]], Heron, Witherington, Medford (later [[Mitford family|Mitford]]), Collingwood, Carnaby, Shaftoe, Ridley, Stokoe, Stamper, Wilkinson, Hunter, [[Thomson (surname)|Thomson]], Jamieson.\n'''''West March'''''\n* Scotland: Bell, [[Clan Irvine|Irvine]], [[Clan Johnstone|Johnstone]], [[Clan Maxwell|Maxwell]], Carlisle, Beattie, [[Clan Little|Little]], [[Clan Carruthers|Carruthers]], Glendenning, Routledge, [[Clan Moffat|Moffat]].\n* England: Graham, [[Hetherington]], Musgrave, Storey, Lowther, Curwen, [[Salkeld]], Dacre, Harden, [[Hodgson]], Routledge, Tailor, Noble.\n\nRelationships between the Border clans varied from uneasy alliance to open, deadly [[feud]]. It took little to start a feud; a chance quarrel or misuse of office was sufficient. Feuds might continue for years until patched up in the face of invasion from the other kingdoms or when the outbreak of other feuds caused alliances to shift. The border was easily destabilised if Graynes from opposite sides of the border were at feud. Feuds also provided ready excuse for particularly murderous raids or pursuits.\n\nRiders did not wear identifying [[tartan]]s. The tradition of family tartans dates from the [[Victorian era|Victorian]] era and was inspired by the novels of [[Sir Walter Scott]]. The typical dress of reivers included [[trews]], [[Jack of plate]], steel bonnets ([[helmet]]s), and [[riding boot]]s.\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Crossing the Tweed on Braw Lad's Day, Galashiels.jpg|thumb|310px|left|Skills of horsemanship are kept alive in the Borders: fording the [[River Tweed]] on Braw Lad's Day, [[Galashiels]] 2011]]\n[[File:Galashiels Reiver Statue 02.JPG|thumb|250px|left|Reiver statue at Galashiels]]\nLong after they were gone, the reivers were romanticised by writers such as [[Sir Walter Scott]] (''[[Minstrelsy of the Scottish Border]]''), although he made mistakes; the term [[Moss-trooper]], which he used, refers to one of the robbers that existed after the real Reivers had been put down. Nevertheless, Scott was a native of the borders, writing down histories which had been passed on in folk tradition or ballad. The stories of legendary border reivers like [[Kinmont Willie Armstrong]] were often retold in folk-song as Border ballads. There are also local legends, such as the \"Dish of Spurs\" which would be served to a border chieftain of the Charltons to remind him that the larder was empty and it was time to acquire more plunder. Scottish author [[Nigel Tranter]] revisited these themes in his historical and contemporary novels.  Scottish Border poet, and Australian bush balladeer, [[William Henry Ogilvie|Will H. Ogilvie]] (1869\u20131963) wrote several poems about the reivers, including ''The reiver's heart'' (1903), ''The raiders'' (1904), ''Whaup o' the rede: a ballad of the border raiders'' (1909), ''[[Kirkhope Tower]]'' (1913), and ''Ho! for the blades of Harden''.\n\nThe names of the [[Reiver]] families are still very much apparent amongst the inhabitants of the [[Scottish Borders]], Northumberland and [[Cumbria]] today. Reiving families (particularly those large or brutal enough to carry significant influence) have left the local population passionate about their territory on both sides of the Border. Newspapers have described the local cross-border rugby fixtures as 'annual re-runs of the bloody [[Battle of Otterburn]]'.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} Despite this there has been much cross-border migration since the Pacification of the Borders, and families that were once Scots now identify themselves as English and vice versa.\n\n[[Hawick]] in Scotland holds an annual Reivers' festival as do the Schomberg Society in Kilkeel, Northern Ireland (the two often co-operate). The summer festival in the Borders town of [[Duns]] is headed by the \"Reiver\" and \"Reiver's Lass\", a young man and young woman elected from the inhabitants of the town and surrounding area. The Ulster-Scots Agency's first two leaflets from the 'Scots Legacy' series feature the story of the historic Ulster tartan and the origins of the kilt and the Border Reivers.\n\nBorderers (particularly those banished by [[James VI of Scotland]]) took part in the [[plantation of Ulster]] becoming the people known as [[Ulster-Scots]] ([[Scotch-Irish American|Scotch-Irish]] in America). Reiver descendants can be found throughout Ulster with names such as Elliot, Armstrong, Beattie, Bell, Carruthers, Hume and Heron, Rutledge, and Turnbulls amongst others.\n\nBorder surnames can also be found throughout the major areas of [[Scots-Irish American|Scotch-Irish]] settlement in the United States, and particularly in the [[Appalachian Mountains|Appalachian]] region. The historian [[David Hackett Fischer]] (1989) has shown in detail how the Anglo-Scottish border culture became rooted in parts of the United States, especially the [[Upland South]]. Author [[George MacDonald Fraser]] wryly observed or imagined Border traits and names among controversial people in modern American history: Presidents [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] and [[Richard Nixon]], among others. It is also noted that, in 1969, a descendant of the Borderers, [[Neil Armstrong]], was the first person to set foot on the moon. In 1972 Armstrong was made a [[Freedom of the city|freeman]] of the town of [[Langholm]] in Scotland, the home of his ancestors.\n\nThe artist [[Gordon Young (artist)|Gordon Young]] created a public art work in Carlisle: ''Cursing Stone and Reiver Pavement'', a nod to [[Gavin Dunbar (archbishop of Glasgow)|Gavin Dunbar]], the Archbishop of Glasgow's 1525 ''Monition of Cursing''.  Names of Reiver families are set into the paving of a walkway which connects [[Tullie House Museum]] to [[Carlisle Castle]] under a main road, and part of the bishop's curse is displayed on a 14-ton granite boulder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gordonyoung.net/carlise_cursingstone.html|title=Cursing Stone & Reiver Pavement / Carlisle, 2001|publisher=Gordon Young|accessdate=23 November 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227133140/http://gordonyoung.net/carlise_cursingstone.html|archivedate=27 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Debatable Lands]]\n* [[History of Northumberland]]\n* ''[[The Borderers]]'' (Television series)\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|last=Carey|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Carey, 1st Earl of Monmouth|title=The Stirring World of Robert Carey, Robert Carey's Memoirs 1577\u20131625|publisher=RippingYarns.com|isbn=1-904466-29-X}}\n* {{cite book|last=Durham|first=Keith|author2=McBride, Angus|title=The Border Reivers: The story of the Anglo-Scottish borderlands|year=1995|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=1-85532-417-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781855324176}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ennis|first=Garth|title=War Stories: Volume 2|year=2006|publisher=Vertigo|isbn=1-4012-1039-2}}\n* {{cite book|last=Fischer|first=David Hackett|authorlink=David Hackett Fischer|title=[[Albion's Seed: Four British Folkways in America]]|year=1989|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford and New York}}\n* {{cite book|last=Howker|first=Janni|authorlink=Janni Howker|title=Martin Farrell|year=1997|publisher=Red Fox|isbn=978-0-09-918161-3}}\n* {{cite book|last=MacDonald Fraser|first=George|authorlink=George MacDonald Fraser|title=The Steel Bonnets|year=1971|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=0-00-272746-3}}\n* {{cite book|last=Moffat|first=Alistair|title=The Reivers|year=2008|publisher=Birlinn|location=Edinburgh|isbn=978-1-84158-674-8}}\n* {{cite book|last=Turnbull|first=Rob|title=The Border Reivers: A stain on the image of Tudor England|publisher=[[Medieval History Magazine]]|volume=4|date=December 2003}}\n* {{cite book|last=Moss|first=Tom|title=Deadlock and Deliverance: The Capture and Rescue of Kinmont Willie Armstrong|year=2007|publisher=Rose Cottage Publications|isbn=978-0-9558016-0-0}}\n* {{cite book|last=Tait|first=Jon|title=Dick the Devil's Bairns: Breaking the Border Mafia|year=2018|publisher=Tredition|isbn=978-3-7482-2361-0}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.borderreivers.co.uk The Border Reivers Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090126155155/http://nwlink.com/~scotlass/border.htm The Border Reivers]\n* [http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~gallgaedhil/ Border Reivers DNA Project]\n* [http://the-border-reivers.co.uk Yet Another Border Reivers Website]\n* [http://www.everymansprey.com The Routledge Reivers]\n* [http://www.reivershistory.co.uk The Capture and Rescue of Kinmont Willie Armstrong]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304074111/http://www.go-britain.com/html/borders_map.htm#borders Borders Map with surnames]\n\n{{Scottish clans}}\n\n[[Category:Anglo-Scottish border]]\n[[Category:History of Europe]]\n[[Category:Border Reivers| ]]\n[[Category:Cavalry]]\n[[Category:History of Cumberland]]\n[[Category:History of Cumbria]]\n[[Category:History of Northumberland]]\n[[Category:Military history of Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Military history of Northumberland]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Scottish Borders]]\n[[Category:History of the Scottish Borders]]\n[[Category:Tudor England]]\n", "name_user": "Ira Leviton", "label": "safe", "comment": "Deleted a duplicate \"the\".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Border_reivers"}
{"title_page": "William Powell and Myrna Loy", "text_new": "'''[[William Powell]]''' (1892\u20131984) and '''[[Myrna Loy]]''' (1905\u20131993) starred in 13 movies together in the 1930s and '40s. (Loy also had an uncredited cameo in their 14th and last film together, ''[[The Senator Was Indiscreet]]'', which starred Powell.) \n\nTheir frequent pairing - always playing a couple - and on-screen chemistry, especially in their six popular Thin Man films, where they played husband and wife [[Nick and Nora Charles]], led many fans to believe they were married in real life.<ref name=NP>{{cite news |url=https://nationalpost.com/afterword/nick-and-noras-infinite-marriage |title=Nick and Nora's Infinite Marriage |author=[[Robert Fulford (journalist)|Robert Fulford]] |date=September 13, 2011 |newspaper=[[National Post]]}}</ref> However, they were only good friends.<ref name=Tribune>{{cite news |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1988-01-10-8803210413-story.html |title=Loy Looks Back |author=Karen Heller |date=January 10, 1988 |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> In a 1988 interview, she explained, \"I think we were too much alike for a romance.\"<ref name=Tribune/>\n\nPowell was already a well-established leading man in Hollywood prior to their teaming, dating back to the silent era, but it was the great success of ''[[The Thin Man (film)|The Thin Man]]'' that made Loy a star.<ref name=NP/><ref name=Tribune/> She almost did not get the role. [[Louis B. Mayer]] had already cast her in ''[[Stamboul Quest]]'', and only agreed to let her play Nora Charles if the picture could be shot in three weeks.<ref name=Tribune/> Director [[W. S. Van Dyke|W. S. \"One Take Woody\" Van Dyke]] only needed 16 days for shooting and two for retakes.<ref name=Tribune/> A [[B movie]], ''The Thin Man'' was a box office and critical hit.\n\n==Filmography==\n[[File:Thin-Man-Loy-Powell-Skippy.jpg|left|thumb|Loy and Powell (and the dog Skippy) in a promotional photo for ''The Thin Man''.]]\n* ''[[Manhattan Melodrama]]'' (1934)\n* ''[[The Thin Man (film)|The Thin Man]]'' (1934)\n* ''[[Evelyn Prentice]]'' (1934)\n* ''[[The Great Ziegfeld]]'' (1936)\n* ''[[Libeled Lady]]'' (1936)\n* ''[[After the Thin Man]]'' (1936)\n* ''[[Double Wedding]]'' (1937)\n* ''[[Another Thin Man]]'' (1939)\n* ''[[I Love You Again]]'' (1940)\n* ''[[Love Crazy (1941 film)|Love Crazy]]'' (1941)\n* ''[[Shadow of the Thin Man]]'' (1941)\n* ''[[The Thin Man Goes Home]]'' (1945)\n* ''[[Song of the Thin Man]]'' (1947)\n* ''[[The Senator Was Indiscreet]]'' (1947)\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Film duos]]\n", "text_old": "'''[[William Powell]]''' (1892\u20131984) and '''[[Myrna Loy]]''' (1905\u20131993) starred in 13 movies together in the 1930s and '40s. (Loy also had an uncredited cameo in their 14th and last film together, ''[[The Senator Was Indiscreet]]'', which starred Powell.) \n\nTheir frequent pairing (always playing a couple) and on-screen chemistry, especially in their six popular Thin Man films, where they played husband and wife [[Nick and Nora Charles]], led many fans to believe they were married in real life.<ref name=NP>{{cite news |url=https://nationalpost.com/afterword/nick-and-noras-infinite-marriage |title=Nick and Nora's Infinite Marriage |author=[[Robert Fulford (journalist)|Robert Fulford]] |date=September 13, 2011 |newspaper=[[National Post]]}}</ref> However, they were only good friends.<ref name=Tribune>{{cite news |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1988-01-10-8803210413-story.html |title=Loy Looks Back |author=Karen Heller |date=January 10, 1988 |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> In a 1988 interview, she explained, \"I think we were too much alike for a romance.\"<ref name=Tribune/>\n\nPowell was already a well-established leading man in Hollywood prior to their teaming, dating back to the silent era, but it was the great success of ''[[The Thin Man (film)|The Thin Man]]'' that made Loy a star.<ref name=NP/><ref name=Tribune/> She almost did not get the role. [[Louis B. Mayer]] had already cast her in ''[[Stamboul Quest]]'', and only agreed to let her play Nora Charles if the picture could be shot in three weeks.<ref name=Tribune/> Director [[W. S. Van Dyke|W. S. \"One Take Woody\" Van Dyke]] only needed 16 days for shooting and two for retakes.<ref name=Tribune/> A [[B movie]], ''The Thin Man'' was a box office and critical hit.\n\n==Filmography==\n[[File:Thin-Man-Loy-Powell-Skippy.jpg|left|thumb|Loy and Powell (and the dog Skippy) in a promotional photo for ''The Thin Man''.]]\n* ''[[Manhattan Melodrama]]'' (1934)\n* ''[[The Thin Man (film)|The Thin Man]]'' (1934)\n* ''[[Evelyn Prentice]]'' (1934)\n* ''[[The Great Ziegfeld]]'' (1936)\n* ''[[Libeled Lady]]'' (1936)\n* ''[[After the Thin Man]]'' (1936)\n* ''[[Double Wedding]]'' (1937)\n* ''[[Another Thin Man]]'' (1939)\n* ''[[I Love You Again]]'' (1940)\n* ''[[Love Crazy (1941 film)|Love Crazy]]'' (1941)\n* ''[[Shadow of the Thin Man]]'' (1941)\n* ''[[The Thin Man Goes Home]]'' (1945)\n* ''[[Song of the Thin Man]]'' (1947)\n* ''[[The Senator Was Indiscreet]]'' (1947)\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Film duos]]\n", "name_user": "Clarityfiend", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:minor tweak", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Powell_and_Myrna_Loy"}
{"title_page": "Foreign relations of the United Arab Emirates", "text_new": "{{Update|inaccurate=yes|date=July 2018}}\n{{Politics of the United Arab Emirates}}\nSince the establishment of the [[United Arab Emirates]] on 2 December 1971, the UAE adopted a balanced foreign policy based on adoption of dialogue, respect of international conventions, commitment to the [[United Nations Charter]] and non-interference of other country's internal affairs, and the settlement of disputes by peaceful means. One of the main anchorers of the UAE\u2019s foreign policy has been building cooperation-based relations with all countries of the world. Substantial development assistance has increased the UAE's stature among recipient states. Most of this foreign aid (in excess of $15 billion) has been to Arab and Muslim countries.\n\n==Multilateral relations==\nUAE has joined the [[United Nations]] and the [[Arab League]] and has established diplomatic relations with more than 60 countries, including [[China]], [[Japan]], [[South Korea]], [[Pakistan]], [[Russia]], [[India]], [[Nepal]], [[United States]], and most [[Western Europe]]an countries. It has played a moderate role within the [[Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries]] (OPEC), the [[Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries]] (OAPEC), the [[United Nations]], and the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] (GCC).\n\nThe UAE believes that the Arab League needs to be restructured to become a viable institution, and would like to increase the strength and interoperability of the GCC defense forces.\n\nThe UAE is a member of the following [[international organizations]]: UN and several of its specialized agencies ([[ICAO]], [[International Labour Organization|ILO]], [[UPU]], [[World Health Organization|WHO]], [[WIPO]]); [[World Bank]], [[International Monetary Fund|IMF]], [[Arab League]], [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]] (OIC), OPEC, Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries, and the [[Non-Aligned Movement]].\n\nIn October 2010, the UAE was granted observer status at the Organisation Internationale de la Francophonie<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.francophonie.org/Emirats-arabes-unis.html?var_recherche=unit%20arab%20emirates|title=\u00c9mirats arabes unis - Organisation internationale de la Francophonie|publisher=|access-date=2011-02-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726063437/http://www.francophonie.org/Emirats-arabes-unis.html?var_recherche=unit%20arab%20emirates|archive-date=2011-07-26|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Africa==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Algeria}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Algeria\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Algeria has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Algiers]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Egypt}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Egypt\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nSince the establishment of UAE in 1971, Egypt and the United Arab Emirates relations were always at a good level and developing at an unprecedented rate. The bond of friendship between the leaders of both countries has reflected on the growing political, economic and cultural ties between them, as a result, UAE ranks first among Arab and foreign countries investing in Egypt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sis.gov.eg/En/Politics/Foreign/EArab/U.A.E/040306030000000002.htm |title=Egypt and U.A.E Relations |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109153827/http://www.sis.gov.eg/En/Politics/Foreign/EArab/U.A.E/040306030000000002.htm |archivedate=2009-01-09 }}</ref> UAE and Egypt maintain a close economic ties and maintain trade between the two countries with imports and exports between the two sides.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Eritrea}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\nThe [[United Arab Emirates]] is a member of the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen| Saudi-led coalition]] against [[Houthi insurgency in Yemen| Houthi rebels in Yemen]]. Foreign Minister [[Osman Saleh Mohammed]] is quoted stating the UAE are using \"logistical facilities at the port and airport\" in the southern city of [[Assab]].<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-36469286|title=Has Eritrea's migration problem been exaggerated?|work=BBC}}</ref> [[Human Rights Watch]] reported that the UAE maintains a detention facility at the Assab base, where it may have transferred high-profile prisoners out of [[Yemen]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/06/22/yemen-uae-backs-abusive-local-forces |publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]] |date=June 22, 2017 |title=Yemen: UAE Backs Abusive Local Forces |quote=Human Rights Watch was not able to verify these claims, but according to lawyers and activists, as well as relatives of men who had been disappeared, the UAE was transferring high-level detainees outside of Yemen. According to one of the activists, about 15 people accused of being members of AQAP or IS-Y had been transferred to the base the UAE has been developing in Eritrea\u2019s port city, Assab, over the past two years. A man whose relatives had been disappeared said at least five officials told him the UAE transferred the men outside of Yemen, including three who said the men were being held in Eritrea.}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Kenya}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Kenya\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n* Kenya has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Nairobi]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Liberia}}||<!--Date started-->||\n* Liberia has a Consulate General in Dubai.\n* Relations with UAE are very good with multiple bilateral agreement signed in 2019.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Libya}}||<!--Date started-->||\nThe UAE maintains a [[forward operating base]] at the Al-Khadim Airport, near [[Marj]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/5726/shadowy-uae-base-in-libya-hosts-attack-aircraft-and-chinese-drones |title=Shadowy UAE Base in Libya Hosts Attack Aircraft and Chinese Drones |first=Tyler |last=Rogoway |date=October 27, 2016 |publisher=The Drive Media, Inc |quote=Some of these nations even have their own forward operating bases in Libya, including a secretive remote airfield operated by the United Arab Emirates and located about 50 miles southeast of Benghazi. Here, the UAE has deployed a pocket air force of heavily armed and armored agricultural planes developed into surveillance and light attack platforms\u2013the AT-802U Border Patrol variant of the Air Tractor and the more capable IOMAX Archangel\u2013in addition to S-70 Blackhawks, and Chinese Wing Loong unmanned aircraft}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/10/28/uae-operating-an-airbase-near-marj-report/ |publisher=[[Libya Herald]] |title=UAE operating an airbase near Marj: report |date=October 26, 2016 |quote=IHS Jane\u2019s says that the UAE is operating propeller-driven AT-802U light aircraft, helicopters and surveillance drones from the Al-Khadim airport to the south-east of Marj and Jardas Al-Abid.}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Senegal}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\nThe United Arab Emirates established an embassy in [[Dakar]] in March 2018, which was unveiled by [[Abdullah Bin Zayed Al Nahyan]].<ref name=\"gulf\">{{cite news |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/uae/government/abdullah-opens-new-uae-embassy-in-senegal-1.2183689 |newspaper=[[Gulf News]] |title=Abdullah opens new UAE Embassy in Senegal |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref> The [[Abu Dhabi Fund for Development]] loaned Senegal $13 million to invest in rural [[solar energy]].<ref name=\"gulf\"/>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Somalia}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Somalia\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Somalia has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.<ref name=\"Gpmomwuats\">{{cite news|title=Prime {{sic|minster|nolink=y}} Omar meets with UAE ambassador to Somalia|url=http://goobjoog.com/english/?p=9018|accessdate=21 January 2015|agency=Goobjoog|date=19 January 2015}}</ref>\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Mogadishu]] and a trade office in [[Somaliland]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://somaliland.ae/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-10-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017001711/http://somaliland.ae/ |archive-date=2018-10-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Tanzania}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Tanzania\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Tanzania has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Dar es Salaam]].\n|}\n\n==Americas==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Argentina}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Argentina has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Buenos Aires]].\n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Belize}}||<!--Date started-->10 December 1991||\nBoth countries established diplomatic relations on December 10, 1991<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mfa.gov.bz/images/documents/DIPLOMATIC%20RELATIONS.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230194831/http://www.mfa.gov.bz/images/documents/DIPLOMATIC%20RELATIONS.pdf |archive-date=2017-12-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref>. \n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Brazil}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Brazil has an embassy in [[Abu Dhabi]].<ref>[http://abudhabi.itamaraty.gov.br/pt-br/ Embassy of Brazil in Abu Dhabi (in English and Portuguese)]</ref>\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Brasilia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uae.org.br/Ingles/default.htm|title=Embassy of the United Arab Emirates in Brazil|accessdate=21 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812102902/http://www.uae.org.br/Ingles/default.htm|archive-date=2014-08-12|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Canada}}||<!--Date started-->1974||See [[Canada\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Canada has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in [[Dubai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/uae-eau/index.aspx?lang=eng|title=Embassy of Canada to United Arab Emirates|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Ottawa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uae-embassy.ae/Embassies/ca|title=UAE Embassy in Ottawa-Home|accessdate=21 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220023024/http://www.uae-embassy.ae/Embassies/ca/|archive-date=2015-02-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Chile}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Chile has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Santiago]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Colombia}}||<!--Date started-->1976||\n\n* Colombia has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Bogot\u00e1]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Mexico}}||<!--Date started-->12 September 1975||See [[Mexico\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Mexico has an embassy in Abu Dhabi<ref>{{cite web|url=http://embamex.sre.gob.mx/emiratosarabesunidos/|title=Embajada de M\u00e9xico en Abu Dhabi, Emiratos \u00c1rabes Unidos|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref> and a trade office in Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.promexico.gob.mx/en/mx/orex|title=ProM\u00e9xico offices abroad|last=ProM\u00e9xico|access-date=2015-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150307062651/http://www.promexico.gob.mx/en/mx/orex|archive-date=2015-03-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Mexico City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esp.uae-embassy.mx/embassy/ambassador-saeed-rashed-al-zaabi/|title=Embajador Saeed Rashed Al Zaabi - Embajada de los EAU en M\u00e9xico|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Peru}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Peru has a consulate-general in [[Dubai]].\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Lima]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|United States}}||<!--Date started-->1972||See [[United Arab Emirates\u2013United States relations]]\n\nThe UAE\u2019s strategic relationship with the United States dates back to the 1990 [[invasion of Kuwait]].  Subsequent to joining the military effort, the two countries signed an agreement in late 1992 allowing for US bases on Emirati soil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/r?frd/cstdy:@field(DOCID+ae0056)|title= Library of Congress, Country Study: United Arab Emirates, Data as of 1993|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref> July 25, 1994, a formal Defense Cooperation Agreement has been in place.<ref>[http://www.usembassy.at/en/download/pdf/uae.pdf CRS Report for Congress, The United Arab Emirates (UAE): Issues for U.S. Policy, May 2005] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090306180853/http://www.usembassy.at/en/download/pdf/uae.pdf |date=March 6, 2009 }}</ref> Ten years later, despite publicly opposing the US led war on Iraq, the UAE permitted a minimal amount of US forces to support the operation from the Al Dhafra air base, [[Jebel Ali]], and naval facilities at [[Fujairah]]. Enhancing security relations, has been a US arms sale in March 2000 to the Emirates, valued at $8 billion and included over $2 billion worth of weapons, munitions, and services.<ref>CRS Report for Congress Pg. 5</ref>\n\nA nuclear deal was signed between the US and the UAE meant to supply nuclear technology, expertise and fuel. Despite international opposition to neighboring Iran\u2019s nuclear developments, the US is confident of the UAE\u2019s compliance with the [[Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty]] and the [[International Atomic Energy Agency]] safeguards to refrain from enriching uranium and extracting plutonium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/meast/01/15/us.uae/|title=U.S.-United Arab Emirates sign nuclear deal|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref> It firmly believes this agreement \"has the potential to usher in an era of responsible nuclear-energy development throughout the Middle East.\u201dGlobal Security.org, \"New U.S.-U.A.E. Deal Raises Eyebrows Amid Concern Over Iran's Nuclear Program,\" January 16, 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/usa/2009/usa-090116-rferl01.htm|title=New U.S.-U.A.E. Deal Raises Eyebrows Amid Concern Over Iran's Nuclear Program|author=John Pike|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nCommercially, the UAE is also the States' largest export market in the Middle East constituting $11.6 billion in exports annually. In March 2005, the US opened negotiations on a free trade agreement and despite intermittent depreciation of currencies in the Persian Gulf area, the UAE dirham remains pegged to the dollar.<ref>Thaindian News, \"Pegged to dollar, Gulf currencies have depreciated: report\", April 7, 2008, http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/world-news/pegged-to-dollar-gulf-currencies-have-depreciated-report_10035374.html</ref> The two countries have also maintained close ties through an exchange of cultural and educational partnerships which include the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum|Guggenheim Museum]], and a number of American Universities opening campuses in the Emirates.<ref>UAE-US Relations: UAE-US Partnerships, {{cite web |url=http://www.uae-us.org/page.cfm?id=99 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229160040/http://uae-us.org/page.cfm?id=99 |archivedate=2008-12-29 }}</ref>\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Washington, DC]] and a consulate-general in [[Boston]], [[Los Angeles]], and [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uae-embassy.org/|title=UAE Embassy in Washington, DC|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n* United States has an embassy in [[Abu Dhabi]] and a consulate-general in [[Dubai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abudhabi.usembassy.gov/|title=Home - Embassy of the United States Abu Dhabi, UAE|accessdate=21 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211230123/http://abudhabi.usembassy.gov/|archive-date=11 February 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Uruguay}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* United Arab Emirates is accredited to Uruguay from its embassy in Buenos Aires, Argentina.\n* Uruguay has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n|}\n\n==Asia==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Afghanistan}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\nRelations between Afghanistan are politically and economically strong. This is because the UAE has a small humanitarian military presence in Afghanistan. UAE troops have been welcomed by the country as allied Muslim soldiers and the Emirati soldiers compliment the Afghan hospitality they encounter.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7318731.stm | work=BBC News | title=Muslim troops help win Afghan minds | date=2008-03-28 | accessdate=2010-04-02}}</ref> Protests from [[Kabul]] arose when the victim in the torture tape with Issa bin Zayed Al Nahyan brutally beating a man who is believed to be an Afghan grain merchant that ripped him off for only $5,000.<ref>[[Human rights in the United Arab Emirates#Torture]]</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Bahrain}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Bahrain\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Bahrain has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Manama]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Bangladesh}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\nThe diplomatic relations between Bangladesh and the United Arab Emirates are strong. The UAE is 2nd largest remittance country for Bangladesh after Saudi Arabia. The UAE also funds a lot of projects in Bangladesh.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|China}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[China\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* China has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Beijing]] and consulates-general in [[Hong Kong]] and [[Shanghai]].\n*The UAE and China have been strong international allies, with significant cooperation across economic, political and cultural aspects.<ref>{{cite news |title=Strong bilateral relations serve the strategic interests of both China and the UAE |url=https://www.thenational.ae/opinion/comment/strong-bilateral-relations-serve-the-strategic-interests-of-both-china-and-the-uae-1.749584 |work=The National |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=UAE to welcome China president Xi Jinping in landmark state visit |url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/government/uae-to-welcome-china-president-xi-jinping-in-landmark-state-visit-1.749538 |work=The National |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Editor |first1=Samir Salama, Associate |title=President Xi's visit a milestone in UAE-China ties, says Chinese ambassador |url=https://gulfnews.com/news/uae/government/president-xi-s-visit-a-milestone-in-uae-china-ties-says-chinese-ambassador-1.2250794 |work=GulfNews |date=13 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Reporter |first1=Sami Zaatari, Staff |title=More and more Chinese make UAE their home |url=https://gulfnews.com/news/uae/society/more-and-more-chinese-make-uae-their-home-1.2250577 |work=GulfNews |date=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|India}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[India\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nUAE enjoys close economic and cultural relations with India. Close maritime contact between India and the [[Arabian Peninsula]] date back to 3rd and 2nd millennium BC.<ref>{{cite book\n  |last = Ganguly\n  |first = D.K.\n  |title = History and Historians in Ancient India\n  |url = https://archive.org/details/historyhistorian00gang\n  |url-access = registration\n  |publisher = Abhinav Publications, 1985\n  |isbn = 0-391-03250-X|year = 1984\n }}</ref> and textile and spice trade between the two countries flourished during most of 1st millennium AD.<ref name=EOI>[http://www.indembassyuae.org/induae_bilateral.phtml  Embassy of India - India-UAE relations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116234839/http://www.indembassyuae.org/induae_bilateral.phtml |date=2013-01-16 }}</ref>\n\nThe discovery of oil allowed the UAE to increase and diversify its trade relations with India. UAE and India are each other's main trading partners. The trade totals over $75 billion (AED275.25 billion).<ref name=\"MainTrade\">{{cite news |url=http://gulfnews.com/business/investment/uae-and-india-sign-crucial-investment-protection-pact-1.1266534 |title=UAE and India sign crucial investment protection pact |newspaper=[[Gulf News]] |date=13 December 2013 |accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref> During the first half of 2010, non-oil trade between India and the UAE stood at US$20.4 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moft.gov.ae/tradeofficeindia/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=99:uae-india-h1-trade-jumps-57-to-204b&catid=42:press-releases&Itemid=106|title=UAE-India H1 trade jumps 57% to $20.4b|publisher=}}{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> UAE is home to more than 1.75 million [[Indians in the United Arab Emirates|Indian expatriates]], making Indians the second largest ethnic group in the nation.<ref>[https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/bgn/5444.htm Background Note:United Arab Emirates], Bureau of Near Eastern Affairs, U.S. Department of State</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Indonesia}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Indonesia\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nThe diplomatic relations between Indonesia and United Arab Emirates are important because both share the solidarity as [[Muslim majority countries]], and both countries recognize the important role of each counterpart in the region. Since the diplomatic relations established in 1976, both countries enjoy a friendly and cordial relationship. Indonesia has an embassy in [[Abu Dhabi]], while the United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Jakarta]]. Both countries are partners in multilateral organizations, such as the [[World Trade Organization]] (WTO), The [[Non-Aligned Movement]] and [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]] (OIC).\nIndonesia uses the UAE as the main gate to enter the Persian Gulf and Middle East market, Indonesia's export to UAE is the largest in the Middle East. Indonesian Government has established the trade and investment representative office to promote its products in United Arab Emirates and the entire Middle East region.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Iran}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Iran\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Iran has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Tehran]]. The embassy is administered by a [[Charg\u00e9s d'affaires|Charg\u00e9s d'affaires en pied]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mofa.gov.ae/EN/DiplomaticMissions/Embassies/Tehran/Ambassador/Pages/Ambassador.aspx|title=EMBASSY OF THE UAE IN TEHRAN|work=UNITED Arab Emirates Ministry of Foreign Relations & International Cooperation|accessdate=20 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920123016/https://www.mofa.gov.ae/EN/DiplomaticMissions/Embassies/Tehran/Ambassador/Pages/Ambassador.aspx|archive-date=20 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n* Iran and United Arab Emirates both claims three islands in the [[Persian Gulf]] ([[Abu Musa]], [[Greater Tunb]], and [[Lesser Tunb]]).\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Iraq}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Iraq\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nThe [[Iraq invasion of Kuwait|Iraqi invasion and occupation of Kuwait]] were a shock to the UAE. For the UAE, the crisis over Kuwait demonstrated a lack of Arab unity on a critical Arab issue. The UAE joined the Arab states that opposed the Iraqi invasion and supported the use of force to compel Iraq's withdrawal of troops from Kuwait.<ref name=FROUAE>{{cite web|url=http://countrystudies.us/persian-gulf-states/91.htm|title=United Arab Emirates - Foreign Relations|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref> Prior to the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], the UAE opposed the US-led invasion.\n\nIn June 2008, the Iraqi government announced that the United Arab Emirates would send an ambassador to [[Baghdad]] within a few days. This would become the first Arab ambassador in Iraq since the kidnapping and murder of the Egyptian Ambassador [[Ihab el-Sherif]] in July 2005.  This announcement was made during a surprise visit by the United Arab Emirates' Foreign Minister [[Abdullah Bin Zayed Al Nahyan|Abdullah bin Zayed Al Nahyan]] to Baghdad on 5 June 2008.  This marked the first time a high-ranking official from a [[Arab States of the Persian Gulf|Gulf state]] visited Iraq since March 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Emirates to send envoy to Baghdad |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7437314.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |date=2008-06-05 |accessdate=2008-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=UAE to name ambassador to Baghdad |url=http://archive.gulfnews.com/articles/08/06/05/10218631.html |newspaper=[[Gulf News]] |date=2008-06-05 |accessdate=2008-06-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205074326/http://archive.gulfnews.com/articles/08/06/05/10218631.html |archivedate=2008-12-05 }}</ref>\n\nOn 31 July 2007 following Iraq victory of the [[Asian Cup]], Sheikh [[Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum]], Vice-President and Prime Minister of the UAE awarded the Iraq National football team 20 million Dhs, ($5.2 million) for capturing the Asian Cup for the first time in the country\u2019s history.<ref>{{cite web |title=Iraq football team awarded 5.5mn |url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/497138-iraq-football-team-awarded-55mn?ln=en |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120728225022/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/497138-iraq-football-team-awarded-55mn?ln=en |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-28 |date=2007-08-01 |accessdate=2008-11-30 }}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Israel}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Israel\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nNeither country have formal diplomatic relations with each other.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Japan}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\nDiplomatic relations between UAE and Japan were established as early as UAE's independence in December 1971.<ref name=MOFAJ>[http://www.mofa.go.jp/region/middle_e/uae/index.html Japan-United Arab Emirates Relations] Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Japan</ref> The two countries had always enjoyed friendly ties and trade between each other, exports from UAE to Japan include [[crude oil]] and [[natural gas]] and imports from Japan to UAE include cars and electronics items.<ref name=\"MOFAJ\"/> \n|-\n|{{Flag|Jordan}}\n|\n|Jordan was the first country to recognize UAE after forming the union in 1971. First commander in Chief in UAE military was Jordanian, and first commander in Zayed Military college was Jordanian as well. Making Jordan effectively one of a key partners of forming the UAE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.addustour.com/articles/1097263?s=e0539eda31b7aa6e3f170317f247a513|title=\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0631\u062f\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a .. \u0639\u0644\u0627\u0642\u0629 \u0645\u062a\u064a\u0646\u0629 \u0631\u0627\u0633\u062e\u0629|last=\u0627\u0644\u0642\u064a\u0633\u064a|first=\u0627\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645 \u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0645\u062c\u064a\u062f|website=\u062c\u0631\u064a\u062f\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0648\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0631\u062f\u0646\u064a\u0629|language=ar|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref>\nThe relationship between UAE and Jordan dates to the 1950s, before UAE gain independence and form the union. Jordan at the time used to aid UAE with educational, military, and health care missions, when UAE was still a barren desert.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nateqnews.com/NewsDetails.aspx?Id=21451|title=\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0641\u064a\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0631\u062a\u064a:\u0627\u0648\u0644 \u062f\u0648\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0639\u062a\u0631\u0641\u062a \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a\u062d\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0631\u062a\u064a \u0647\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0631\u062f\u0646|date=2017-12-02|website=\u0648\u0643\u0627\u0644\u0629 \u0646\u0627\u0637\u0642 \u0646\u064a\u0648\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u062e\u0628\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0629|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Kuwait}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Kuwait\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Kuwait has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Kuwait City]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Malaysia}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Malaysia\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nUnited Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Kuala Lumpur]], and Malaysia has an embassy in [[Abu Dhabi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kln.gov.my/perwakilan/abudhabi|title=Redirecting|accessdate=21 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221195512/http://www.kln.gov.my/perwakilan/abudhabi/|archive-date=2015-02-21|url-status=dead}}</ref> The countries established diplomatic relations in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/malaysia/mt_eco_cnt1.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-07-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081117180304/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/malaysia/mt_eco_cnt1.html |archivedate=2008-11-17 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005 Malaysia\u2019s export to the UAE stood at Dh7 billion. Main export items were gold and jewellery, wood products (furniture and parts), palm oil, petroleum products and electrical appliances. In 2007, trade between Malaysia and UAE was worth [[Malaysian ringgit|MYR]] 14.56 billion making UAE, Malaysia's largest trading partner in West Asia as well as Malaysia being the 10th largest exporter to UAE.<ref>http://www.bernama.com/bernama/v5/newsindex.php?id=340777</ref> In 2009, Malaysian ambassador Datuk Yahaya Abdul Jabar said total trade between Malaysia and UAE from January to November stood at RM19.5 billion. Malaysia's main exports to the UAE are jewellery, consumer electronics and palm oil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hailplaza.com|title=hailpaza.com|publisher=}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|North Korea }}||<!--Date started-->2007-09-19<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mobacle.blog.me/70022240636|title=\ubbf8\ub798\uc0ac\ud68c (FUSO) : \ub124\uc774\ubc84 \ube14\ub85c\uadf8|publisher=}}</ref> Relations ended 2007-10-12<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-missiles-emirates/uae-terminates-north-korean-diplomatic-mission-ends-visas-idUSKBN1CH247}}</ref>\n\nhttps://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-missiles-emirates/uae-terminates-north-korean-diplomatic-mission-ends-visas-idUSKBN1CH247\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Oman}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Oman\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Oman has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Muscat]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Pakistan}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Pakistan\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nPakistan and the UAE are very close allies with extremely close relations based on cultural affinities and shared [[Islam|faith]]. These relations date back to the UAE's formation in 1971, and have since developed into wide-ranging co-operation in various fields. UAE has been a major donor of economic assistance to Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pakobserver.net/200811/26/Editorial01.asp |title=Relations with UAE get wider, deeper |accessdate=December 26, 2008 |publisher=[[Pakistan Observer]] |date=November 26, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090626001001/http://pakobserver.net/200811/26/Editorial01.asp |archivedate=June 26, 2009 }}</ref> [[Shaikh Zayed International Airport (Rahim Yar Khan)|Sheikh Zayed International Airport]] in [[Rahim Yar Khan]], in the [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab province]] of Pakistan is an example of UAE's economic assistance as the late president and the founder of the UAE [[Sheikh Zayed]] donated the airport to the government of Pakistan.\n\nUAE has emerged as one of Pakistan's major economic and trading partners. A large number of Pakistani expatriates, numbering nearly 1.2 million are gainfully employed in UAE.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Qatar }}||'''Dipolmatic relations severed on 5 June 2017'''||See [[Qatar\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nIn 5 June 2017, the government of United Arab Emirates severed diplomatic ties with Qatar on accounts of [[Qatar and state-sponsored terrorism#2017 diplomatic crisis|Qatar's financial support for terrorism]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/06/05/middleeast/saudi-bahrain-egypt-uae-qatar-terror/index.html|title=Qatar rift: Saudi, UAE, Bahrain, Egypt cut diplomatic ties|publisher=CNN|date=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Russia}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Russia\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Russia has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Moscow]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Saudi Arabia}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Saudi Arabia\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Saudi Arabia has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Riyadh]] and a consulate-general in [[Jeddah]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|South Korea }}||<!--Date started-->18 June 1980<ref name=\"mofa.go.kr\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20150904015758/http://www.mofa.go.kr/ENG/countries/middleeast/countries/20070824/1_24424.jsp?menu=m_30_50 Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Republic of Korea-Middle East and Africa<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> ||\n* The establishment of diplomatic relations between the United Arab Emirates and the Republic of Korea began on 18 June 1980. \n* UAE is the 3rd largest exporter of oil to South Korea (108,000,000 barrels 2014).\n* The United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Seoul]].\n* South Korea has an embassy [[Abu Dhabi]].<ref name=\"mofa.go.kr\"/> \n|}\n\n==Europe==\nThe UAE\u2019s liberal climate towards foreign cooperation, investment and modernization have prompted extensive commercial ties with western countries, and subsequently resulting in even closer cultural relations.  The country remains a major global tourist and foreign direct investment destination but a few countries play a more significant role than the rest.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Albania}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Albania has an embassy in [[Abu Dhabi]].\n* United Arab Emirates is accredited to Albania from its embassy in [[Rome]], [[Italy]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Armenia}}||<!--Date started-->||\n* Diplomatic relations between Armenia and the UAE were established on June 25, 1998.\n* Armenia has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* The United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Yerevan]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Denmark}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Denmark\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Denmark has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates is accredited to Denmark from its embassy in [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|France}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[France\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nThe UAE\u2019s relationship with France has been strategically important as it negotiated a defence cooperation agreement and remains one of the country\u2019s primary providers of military material.<ref name=\"LOCCP:UAE\">Library of Congress Country Profile: UAE, http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/profiles/UAE.pdf</ref> France and the UAE have signed a defence cooperation agreement in order to diversity its procurement from solely the US.<ref name=\"LOCCP:UAE\"/> Culturally, as the [[Sorbonne]] and [[Louvre]] are both establishing extensions in the UAE,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2007-03-06-louvre-abu-dhabi_N.htm|title=Louvre museum to build branch in UAE - USATODAY.com|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref> a plan is in the works to recreate a miniature [[Lyon]] city in Dubai complete with public squares, restaurants and museums.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulfnews.com/Nation/Government/10214894.html|title=UAE and France share strong bilateral relations|accessdate=21 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202194826/http://www.gulfnews.com/nation/Government/10214894.html|archive-date=2008-12-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn May 25, 2009, the French president [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] visited the UAE, Abu Dhabi where he along with UAE's president H.H Sheikh Khalifa Bin Zayed Al Nahyan formally opened a French military base in the United Arab Emirates. This would become France's first permanent base in the Persian Gulf, hosting up to 500 French troops.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/8067600.stm|title=French President Sarkozy opens UAE base|accessdate=January 10, 2009 |work=BBC|date=May 26, 2009}}</ref> In addition to the inauguration of Peace Camp, Nicolas Sarkozy visited the site of a [[Louvre Abu Dhabi|Louvre Museum branch]] which France is opening in the United Arab Emirates. Sheikh Abdullah bin Zayed Al Nahyan, Minister of Foreign Affairs, said that the co-operation with France is a top priority for the UAE's foreign policy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gulfnews.com/nation/government/10317048.html|title=Relationship with France is top priority for UAE, Abdullah says|accessdate=January 10, 2009|work=Gulf News|date=May 26, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090528114021/http://www.gulfnews.com/nation/Government/10317048.html|archive-date=2009-05-28|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Georgia}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\nDiplomatic relations between [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and the UAE were initiated on 20 October 1992.<ref name=mofag>{{cite web|title=Relations Between Georgia and the United Arab Emirates|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Georgia)}}</ref> The countries are represented in each other through embassies.<ref name=mofag/> \n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Germany}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Germany\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nGerman exports amount to 5.84 billion Euros.<ref>[http://www.auswaertiges-amt.de/diplo/en/Laenderinformationen/01-Laender/VAE.html Federal Foreign Office of Germany] Country Profile UAE, October 2008</ref> German companies significantly contribute to the UAE\u2019s ongoing infrastructure projects and play a leading role in the country\u2019s alternative energy developments.<ref>[http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentID=2008103120686 \"UAE, Germany to cooperate in averting financial mayhem\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716184614/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentID=2008103120686 |date=July 16, 2011 }} ''Saudi Gazette''.</ref> Consequently, German [[Business Park]], an area designed to house several of the already seven hundred present companies and their logistical needs, is in the midst of construction.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dso.ae/en/news/german-business-park.html |title=Dubai Silicon Oasis Authority, Website News Release, October 2007 |access-date=2009-02-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090321172108/http://www.dso.ae/en/news/german-business-park.html |archive-date=2009-03-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Greece}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Greece\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Greece has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Athens]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Ireland}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Ireland has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Dublin]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Kosovo}}||14 October 2008<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wam.org.ae/servlet/Satellite?c=WamLocEnews&cid=1223546208865&p=1135099400124&pagename=WAM%2FWamLocEnews%2FW-T-LEN-FullNews |title=UAE recognises Kosovo |publisher=[[Emirates News Agency]] |date=2008-10-14 |accessdate=2008-10-14 |quote=In accordance with its firm support for the principle of the legitimate right of peoples to self-determination, the United Arab Emirates has announced its recognition of the Kosovo Republic as an independent and sovereign state. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081017065840/http://www.wam.org.ae/servlet/Satellite?c=WamLocEnews&cid=1223546208865&p=1135099400124&pagename=WAM%2FWamLocEnews%2FW-T-LEN-FullNews |archivedate=2008-10-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.africasia.com/services/news/newsitem.php?area=mideast&item=081014155526.3e2km83b.php|title=UAE recognises Kosovo|publisher=IC Publications|date=2008-10-14|accessdate=2008-10-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022221352/http://www.africasia.com/services/news/newsitem.php?area=mideast&item=081014155526.3e2km83b.php|archive-date=2008-10-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>||See [[Kosovo\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Kosovo has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/kosovo-moldova-open-embassies-in-abu-dhabi-1.2220793|title=Kosovo, Moldova open embassies in Abu Dhabi|newspaper=Gulf News|date=13 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gazetaexpress.com/en/news/kosovo-opens-embassy-in-uae-174092/|title=Kosovo opens embassy in UAE|publisher=Gazeta Express|date=10 May 2018|access-date=15 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181216031421/https://www.gazetaexpress.com/en/news/kosovo-opens-embassy-in-uae-174092/|archive-date=16 December 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* United Arab Emirates is accredited to Kosovo from its embassy in [[Ankara]], [[Turkey]].\n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|North Macedonia}}||<!--Date started-->||\nNorth Macedonia has an embassy in [[Abu Dhabi]]<ref>[http://www.mfa.gov.mk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=429&Itemid=751&lang=en#dkpazija]</ref>. \n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Poland}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Poland has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Warsaw]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Serbia}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Serbia\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nRelations between Serbia and the United Arab Emirates have flourished in recent years. Serbia has an embassy in Abu Dhabi, and the UAE has an embassy in [[Belgrade]]. The UAE is now one of the top sources of FDI for Serbia.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Spain}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Spain has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a commercial office in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Madrid]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Ukraine}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Ukraine has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Kiev]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|United Kingdom}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[United Arab Emirates\u2013United Kingdom relations]]\n\nTraditionally, links between the sheikhs of the lower Gulf and the United Kingdom were close as a result of a series of 19th-century maritime truces for the suppression of piracy. Since the British withdrew their military forces from the Persian Gulf in 1971, relations have remained friendly while the UAE has reorientated its foreign policy away from the former \"colonial\" relationship to one based on trade. Economically, the UAE is the UK\u2019s largest export market for non-military goods in the Middle East.<ref>British Foreign And Commonwealth Office, Country Profile: UAE; January 2009 {{cite web |url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/middle-east-north-africa/united-arab-emirates?profile=intRelations&pg=4 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081228153759/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/middle-east-north-africa/united-arab-emirates/?profile=intRelations&pg=4 |archivedate=2008-12-28 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Oceania==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Australia}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Australia\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nThe UAE and Australia have begun establishing closer relations, recently the UAE Minister of Economy, Sultan Bin Saeed Al Mansouri visited Australia along with the UAE delegation - discussion focused on the development of a strategic partnership, financial services, trade and investment.<ref>[http://www.wam.org.ae/servlet/Satellite?c=WamLocEnews&cid=1289993206373&p=1135099400124&pagename=WAM%2FWamLocEnews%2FW-T-LEN-FullNews UAE is strategic partner and a gateway for Australia to the Middle East, says Al Mansouri] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721081016/http://www.wam.org.ae/servlet/Satellite?c=WamLocEnews&cid=1289993206373&p=1135099400124&pagename=WAM%2FWamLocEnews%2FW-T-LEN-FullNews |date=July 21, 2011 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.wam.org.ae/servlet/Satellite?c=WamLocEnews&cid=1289993219934&p=1135099400124&pagename=WAM%2FWamLocEnews%2FW-T-LEN-FullNews UAE to forger closer economic ties Australia: Al-Mansouri] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721081034/http://www.wam.org.ae/servlet/Satellite?c=WamLocEnews&cid=1289993219934&p=1135099400124&pagename=WAM%2FWamLocEnews%2FW-T-LEN-FullNews |date=July 21, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/biz/inside.asp?xfile=/data/business/2011/April/business_April428.xml&section=business|title=UAE a gateway for Australia to ME: Mansouri - Khaleej Times|first=(Staff|last=Report)|publisher=}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|New Zealand}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* New Zealand has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Wellington]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Solomon Islands}}||<!--Date started-->2010||\nBoth countries established diplomatic relations on April 29, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wam.ae/en/details/1395228642109|title=UAE and Solomon Islands establish diplomatic relations|publisher=}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Tuvalu}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\nThe UAE and Tuvalu established diplomatic relations on 31 March 2010.<ref>[http://www.wam.org.ae/servlet/Satellite?c=WamLocEnews&cid=1267001043764&p=1135099400124&pagename=WAM%2FWamLocEnews%2FW-T-LEN-FullNews \"UAE and Tuvalu establish diplomatic relations\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203034816/http://www.wam.org.ae/servlet/Satellite?c=WamLocEnews&cid=1267001043764&p=1135099400124&pagename=WAM%2FWamLocEnews%2FW-T-LEN-FullNews |date=February 3, 2014 }} 31 March 2010 Link retrieved 01 April 2010</ref>\n|}\n\n==International disputes==\n{{See also|Territorial disputes in the Persian Gulf}}\n*Location and status of boundary with [[Saudi Arabia]] is not final, de facto boundary reflects 1974 agreement; no defined boundary with most of [[Oman]], but Administrative Line in far north;\n*Claims three islands in the [[Persian Gulf]] that are part of [[Iran]]'s territory: Lesser Tunb (called Tunb as Sughra in Arabic by UAE and Jazireh-ye Tonb-e Kuchak in Persian by Iran) and Greater Tunb (called Tunb al Kubra in Arabic by UAE and Jazireh-ye Tonb-e Bozorg in Persian by Iran);\n*Claims island in the Persian Gulf administered by Iran (called Abu Musa in Arabic by UAE and Jazireh-ye Abu Musa in Persian by Iran) - over which Iran has taken steps to exert unilateral control since 1992, including access restrictions and a military build-up on the island;\n\n==Illicit drugs==\nThe UAE plays a growing role as a [[drug trafficking]] center due to its proximity to southwest Asian producing countries and the bustling free trade zone in [[Dubai]]. As a result, the UAE has one of the strongest anti-drug law enforcement, and the penalty of drug possession is severe. The UAE ministry of foreign affairs warns tourists of UAE drug laws before entering the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tourists Warned of UAE Drug and Prescription Medication Laws |url=http://forum.virtualtourist.com/discussion-402276-1-1-Travel-0-0-Dubai-discussion.html |date=February 10, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of diplomatic missions in the United Arab Emirates]]\n* [[List of diplomatic missions of the United Arab Emirates]]\n* [[Visa requirements for United Arab Emirati citizens]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090221130621/http://mofa.gov.ae/ Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the United Arab Emirates] {{in lang|ar}}\n\n{{Foreign relations of the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Asia topic|Foreign relations of}}\n{{United Arab Emirates topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foreign Relations Of The United Arab Emirates}}\n[[Category:Foreign relations of the United Arab Emirates| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Update|inaccurate=yes|date=July 2018}}\n{{Politics of the United Arab Emirates}}\nSince the establishment of the [[United Arab Emirates]] on 2 December 1971, the UAE adopted a balanced foreign policy based on adoption of dialogue, respect of international conventions, commitment to the [[United Nations Charter]] and non-interference of other country's internal affairs, and the settlement of disputes by peaceful means\n\nOne of the main anchorers of the UAE\u2019s foreign policy has been building cooperation-based relations with all countries of the world. Substantial development assistance has increased the UAE's stature among recipient states. Most of this foreign aid (in excess of $15 billion) has been to Arab and Muslim countries.\n\n==Multilateral relations==\nUAE has joined the [[United Nations]] and the [[Arab League]] and has established diplomatic relations with more than 60 countries, including [[China]], [[Japan]], [[South Korea]], [[Pakistan]], [[Russia]], [[India]], [[Nepal]], [[United States]], and most [[Western Europe]]an countries. It has played a moderate role within the [[Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries]] (OPEC), the [[Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries]] (OAPEC), the [[United Nations]], and the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] (GCC).\n\nThe UAE believes that the Arab League needs to be restructured to become a viable institution, and would like to increase the strength and interoperability of the GCC defense forces.\n\nThe UAE is a member of the following [[international organizations]]: UN and several of its specialized agencies ([[ICAO]], [[International Labour Organization|ILO]], [[UPU]], [[World Health Organization|WHO]], [[WIPO]]); [[World Bank]], [[International Monetary Fund|IMF]], [[Arab League]], [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]] (OIC), OPEC, Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries, and the [[Non-Aligned Movement]].\n\nIn October 2010, the UAE was granted observer status at the Organisation Internationale de la Francophonie<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.francophonie.org/Emirats-arabes-unis.html?var_recherche=unit%20arab%20emirates|title=\u00c9mirats arabes unis - Organisation internationale de la Francophonie|publisher=|access-date=2011-02-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726063437/http://www.francophonie.org/Emirats-arabes-unis.html?var_recherche=unit%20arab%20emirates|archive-date=2011-07-26|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Africa==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Algeria}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Algeria\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Algeria has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Algiers]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Egypt}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Egypt\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nSince the establishment of UAE in 1971, Egypt and the United Arab Emirates relations were always at a good level and developing at an unprecedented rate. The bond of friendship between the leaders of both countries has reflected on the growing political, economic and cultural ties between them, as a result, UAE ranks first among Arab and foreign countries investing in Egypt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sis.gov.eg/En/Politics/Foreign/EArab/U.A.E/040306030000000002.htm |title=Egypt and U.A.E Relations |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109153827/http://www.sis.gov.eg/En/Politics/Foreign/EArab/U.A.E/040306030000000002.htm |archivedate=2009-01-09 }}</ref> UAE and Egypt maintain a close economic ties and maintain trade between the two countries with imports and exports between the two sides.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Eritrea}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\nThe [[United Arab Emirates]] is a member of the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen| Saudi-led coalition]] against [[Houthi insurgency in Yemen| Houthi rebels in Yemen]]. Foreign Minister [[Osman Saleh Mohammed]] is quoted stating the UAE are using \"logistical facilities at the port and airport\" in the southern city of [[Assab]].<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-36469286|title=Has Eritrea's migration problem been exaggerated?|work=BBC}}</ref> [[Human Rights Watch]] reported that the UAE maintains a detention facility at the Assab base, where it may have transferred high-profile prisoners out of [[Yemen]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/06/22/yemen-uae-backs-abusive-local-forces |publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]] |date=June 22, 2017 |title=Yemen: UAE Backs Abusive Local Forces |quote=Human Rights Watch was not able to verify these claims, but according to lawyers and activists, as well as relatives of men who had been disappeared, the UAE was transferring high-level detainees outside of Yemen. According to one of the activists, about 15 people accused of being members of AQAP or IS-Y had been transferred to the base the UAE has been developing in Eritrea\u2019s port city, Assab, over the past two years. A man whose relatives had been disappeared said at least five officials told him the UAE transferred the men outside of Yemen, including three who said the men were being held in Eritrea.}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Kenya}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Kenya\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n* Kenya has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Nairobi]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Liberia}}||<!--Date started-->||\n* Liberia has a Consulate General in Dubai.\n* Relations with UAE are very good with multiple bilateral agreement signed in 2019.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Libya}}||<!--Date started-->||\nThe UAE maintains a [[forward operating base]] at the Al-Khadim Airport, near [[Marj]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/5726/shadowy-uae-base-in-libya-hosts-attack-aircraft-and-chinese-drones |title=Shadowy UAE Base in Libya Hosts Attack Aircraft and Chinese Drones |first=Tyler |last=Rogoway |date=October 27, 2016 |publisher=The Drive Media, Inc |quote=Some of these nations even have their own forward operating bases in Libya, including a secretive remote airfield operated by the United Arab Emirates and located about 50 miles southeast of Benghazi. Here, the UAE has deployed a pocket air force of heavily armed and armored agricultural planes developed into surveillance and light attack platforms\u2013the AT-802U Border Patrol variant of the Air Tractor and the more capable IOMAX Archangel\u2013in addition to S-70 Blackhawks, and Chinese Wing Loong unmanned aircraft}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2016/10/28/uae-operating-an-airbase-near-marj-report/ |publisher=[[Libya Herald]] |title=UAE operating an airbase near Marj: report |date=October 26, 2016 |quote=IHS Jane\u2019s says that the UAE is operating propeller-driven AT-802U light aircraft, helicopters and surveillance drones from the Al-Khadim airport to the south-east of Marj and Jardas Al-Abid.}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Senegal}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\nThe United Arab Emirates established an embassy in [[Dakar]] in March 2018, which was unveiled by [[Abdullah Bin Zayed Al Nahyan]].<ref name=\"gulf\">{{cite news |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/uae/government/abdullah-opens-new-uae-embassy-in-senegal-1.2183689 |newspaper=[[Gulf News]] |title=Abdullah opens new UAE Embassy in Senegal |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref> The [[Abu Dhabi Fund for Development]] loaned Senegal $13 million to invest in rural [[solar energy]].<ref name=\"gulf\"/>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Somalia}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Somalia\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Somalia has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.<ref name=\"Gpmomwuats\">{{cite news|title=Prime {{sic|minster|nolink=y}} Omar meets with UAE ambassador to Somalia|url=http://goobjoog.com/english/?p=9018|accessdate=21 January 2015|agency=Goobjoog|date=19 January 2015}}</ref>\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Mogadishu]] and a trade office in [[Somaliland]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://somaliland.ae/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-10-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017001711/http://somaliland.ae/ |archive-date=2018-10-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Tanzania}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Tanzania\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Tanzania has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Dar es Salaam]].\n|}\n\n==Americas==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Argentina}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Argentina has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Buenos Aires]].\n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Belize}}||<!--Date started-->10 December 1991||\nBoth countries established diplomatic relations on December 10, 1991<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mfa.gov.bz/images/documents/DIPLOMATIC%20RELATIONS.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230194831/http://www.mfa.gov.bz/images/documents/DIPLOMATIC%20RELATIONS.pdf |archive-date=2017-12-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref>. \n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Brazil}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Brazil has an embassy in [[Abu Dhabi]].<ref>[http://abudhabi.itamaraty.gov.br/pt-br/ Embassy of Brazil in Abu Dhabi (in English and Portuguese)]</ref>\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Brasilia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uae.org.br/Ingles/default.htm|title=Embassy of the United Arab Emirates in Brazil|accessdate=21 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812102902/http://www.uae.org.br/Ingles/default.htm|archive-date=2014-08-12|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Canada}}||<!--Date started-->1974||See [[Canada\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Canada has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in [[Dubai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/uae-eau/index.aspx?lang=eng|title=Embassy of Canada to United Arab Emirates|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Ottawa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uae-embassy.ae/Embassies/ca|title=UAE Embassy in Ottawa-Home|accessdate=21 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220023024/http://www.uae-embassy.ae/Embassies/ca/|archive-date=2015-02-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Chile}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Chile has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Santiago]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Colombia}}||<!--Date started-->1976||\n\n* Colombia has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Bogot\u00e1]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Mexico}}||<!--Date started-->12 September 1975||See [[Mexico\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Mexico has an embassy in Abu Dhabi<ref>{{cite web|url=http://embamex.sre.gob.mx/emiratosarabesunidos/|title=Embajada de M\u00e9xico en Abu Dhabi, Emiratos \u00c1rabes Unidos|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref> and a trade office in Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.promexico.gob.mx/en/mx/orex|title=ProM\u00e9xico offices abroad|last=ProM\u00e9xico|access-date=2015-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150307062651/http://www.promexico.gob.mx/en/mx/orex|archive-date=2015-03-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Mexico City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esp.uae-embassy.mx/embassy/ambassador-saeed-rashed-al-zaabi/|title=Embajador Saeed Rashed Al Zaabi - Embajada de los EAU en M\u00e9xico|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Peru}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Peru has a consulate-general in [[Dubai]].\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Lima]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|United States}}||<!--Date started-->1972||See [[United Arab Emirates\u2013United States relations]]\n\nThe UAE\u2019s strategic relationship with the United States dates back to the 1990 [[invasion of Kuwait]].  Subsequent to joining the military effort, the two countries signed an agreement in late 1992 allowing for US bases on Emirati soil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/r?frd/cstdy:@field(DOCID+ae0056)|title= Library of Congress, Country Study: United Arab Emirates, Data as of 1993|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref> July 25, 1994, a formal Defense Cooperation Agreement has been in place.<ref>[http://www.usembassy.at/en/download/pdf/uae.pdf CRS Report for Congress, The United Arab Emirates (UAE): Issues for U.S. Policy, May 2005] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090306180853/http://www.usembassy.at/en/download/pdf/uae.pdf |date=March 6, 2009 }}</ref> Ten years later, despite publicly opposing the US led war on Iraq, the UAE permitted a minimal amount of US forces to support the operation from the Al Dhafra air base, [[Jebel Ali]], and naval facilities at [[Fujairah]]. Enhancing security relations, has been a US arms sale in March 2000 to the Emirates, valued at $8 billion and included over $2 billion worth of weapons, munitions, and services.<ref>CRS Report for Congress Pg. 5</ref>\n\nA nuclear deal was signed between the US and the UAE meant to supply nuclear technology, expertise and fuel. Despite international opposition to neighboring Iran\u2019s nuclear developments, the US is confident of the UAE\u2019s compliance with the [[Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty]] and the [[International Atomic Energy Agency]] safeguards to refrain from enriching uranium and extracting plutonium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/meast/01/15/us.uae/|title=U.S.-United Arab Emirates sign nuclear deal|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref> It firmly believes this agreement \"has the potential to usher in an era of responsible nuclear-energy development throughout the Middle East.\u201dGlobal Security.org, \"New U.S.-U.A.E. Deal Raises Eyebrows Amid Concern Over Iran's Nuclear Program,\" January 16, 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/usa/2009/usa-090116-rferl01.htm|title=New U.S.-U.A.E. Deal Raises Eyebrows Amid Concern Over Iran's Nuclear Program|author=John Pike|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nCommercially, the UAE is also the States' largest export market in the Middle East constituting $11.6 billion in exports annually. In March 2005, the US opened negotiations on a free trade agreement and despite intermittent depreciation of currencies in the Persian Gulf area, the UAE dirham remains pegged to the dollar.<ref>Thaindian News, \"Pegged to dollar, Gulf currencies have depreciated: report\", April 7, 2008, http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/world-news/pegged-to-dollar-gulf-currencies-have-depreciated-report_10035374.html</ref> The two countries have also maintained close ties through an exchange of cultural and educational partnerships which include the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum|Guggenheim Museum]], and a number of American Universities opening campuses in the Emirates.<ref>UAE-US Relations: UAE-US Partnerships, {{cite web |url=http://www.uae-us.org/page.cfm?id=99 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229160040/http://uae-us.org/page.cfm?id=99 |archivedate=2008-12-29 }}</ref>\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Washington, DC]] and a consulate-general in [[Boston]], [[Los Angeles]], and [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uae-embassy.org/|title=UAE Embassy in Washington, DC|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n* United States has an embassy in [[Abu Dhabi]] and a consulate-general in [[Dubai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abudhabi.usembassy.gov/|title=Home - Embassy of the United States Abu Dhabi, UAE|accessdate=21 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211230123/http://abudhabi.usembassy.gov/|archive-date=11 February 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Uruguay}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* United Arab Emirates is accredited to Uruguay from its embassy in Buenos Aires, Argentina.\n* Uruguay has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n|}\n\n==Asia==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Afghanistan}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\nRelations between Afghanistan are politically and economically strong. This is because the UAE has a small humanitarian military presence in Afghanistan. UAE troops have been welcomed by the country as allied Muslim soldiers and the Emirati soldiers compliment the Afghan hospitality they encounter.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7318731.stm | work=BBC News | title=Muslim troops help win Afghan minds | date=2008-03-28 | accessdate=2010-04-02}}</ref> Protests from [[Kabul]] arose when the victim in the torture tape with Issa bin Zayed Al Nahyan brutally beating a man who is believed to be an Afghan grain merchant that ripped him off for only $5,000.<ref>[[Human rights in the United Arab Emirates#Torture]]</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Bahrain}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Bahrain\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Bahrain has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Manama]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Bangladesh}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\nThe diplomatic relations between Bangladesh and the United Arab Emirates are strong. The UAE is 2nd largest remittance country for Bangladesh after Saudi Arabia. The UAE also funds a lot of projects in Bangladesh.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|China}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[China\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* China has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Beijing]] and consulates-general in [[Hong Kong]] and [[Shanghai]].\n*The UAE and China have been strong international allies, with significant cooperation across economic, political and cultural aspects.<ref>{{cite news |title=Strong bilateral relations serve the strategic interests of both China and the UAE |url=https://www.thenational.ae/opinion/comment/strong-bilateral-relations-serve-the-strategic-interests-of-both-china-and-the-uae-1.749584 |work=The National |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=UAE to welcome China president Xi Jinping in landmark state visit |url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/government/uae-to-welcome-china-president-xi-jinping-in-landmark-state-visit-1.749538 |work=The National |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Editor |first1=Samir Salama, Associate |title=President Xi's visit a milestone in UAE-China ties, says Chinese ambassador |url=https://gulfnews.com/news/uae/government/president-xi-s-visit-a-milestone-in-uae-china-ties-says-chinese-ambassador-1.2250794 |work=GulfNews |date=13 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Reporter |first1=Sami Zaatari, Staff |title=More and more Chinese make UAE their home |url=https://gulfnews.com/news/uae/society/more-and-more-chinese-make-uae-their-home-1.2250577 |work=GulfNews |date=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|India}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[India\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nUAE enjoys close economic and cultural relations with India. Close maritime contact between India and the [[Arabian Peninsula]] date back to 3rd and 2nd millennium BC.<ref>{{cite book\n  |last = Ganguly\n  |first = D.K.\n  |title = History and Historians in Ancient India\n  |url = https://archive.org/details/historyhistorian00gang\n  |url-access = registration\n  |publisher = Abhinav Publications, 1985\n  |isbn = 0-391-03250-X|year = 1984\n }}</ref> and textile and spice trade between the two countries flourished during most of 1st millennium AD.<ref name=EOI>[http://www.indembassyuae.org/induae_bilateral.phtml  Embassy of India - India-UAE relations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116234839/http://www.indembassyuae.org/induae_bilateral.phtml |date=2013-01-16 }}</ref>\n\nThe discovery of oil allowed the UAE to increase and diversify its trade relations with India. UAE and India are each other's main trading partners. The trade totals over $75 billion (AED275.25 billion).<ref name=\"MainTrade\">{{cite news |url=http://gulfnews.com/business/investment/uae-and-india-sign-crucial-investment-protection-pact-1.1266534 |title=UAE and India sign crucial investment protection pact |newspaper=[[Gulf News]] |date=13 December 2013 |accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref> During the first half of 2010, non-oil trade between India and the UAE stood at US$20.4 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moft.gov.ae/tradeofficeindia/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=99:uae-india-h1-trade-jumps-57-to-204b&catid=42:press-releases&Itemid=106|title=UAE-India H1 trade jumps 57% to $20.4b|publisher=}}{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> UAE is home to more than 1.75 million [[Indians in the United Arab Emirates|Indian expatriates]], making Indians the second largest ethnic group in the nation.<ref>[https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/bgn/5444.htm Background Note:United Arab Emirates], Bureau of Near Eastern Affairs, U.S. Department of State</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Indonesia}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Indonesia\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nThe diplomatic relations between Indonesia and United Arab Emirates are important because both share the solidarity as [[Muslim majority countries]], and both countries recognize the important role of each counterpart in the region. Since the diplomatic relations established in 1976, both countries enjoy a friendly and cordial relationship. Indonesia has an embassy in [[Abu Dhabi]], while the United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Jakarta]]. Both countries are partners in multilateral organizations, such as the [[World Trade Organization]] (WTO), The [[Non-Aligned Movement]] and [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]] (OIC).\nIndonesia uses the UAE as the main gate to enter the Persian Gulf and Middle East market, Indonesia's export to UAE is the largest in the Middle East. Indonesian Government has established the trade and investment representative office to promote its products in United Arab Emirates and the entire Middle East region.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Iran}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Iran\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Iran has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Tehran]]. The embassy is administered by a [[Charg\u00e9s d'affaires|Charg\u00e9s d'affaires en pied]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mofa.gov.ae/EN/DiplomaticMissions/Embassies/Tehran/Ambassador/Pages/Ambassador.aspx|title=EMBASSY OF THE UAE IN TEHRAN|work=UNITED Arab Emirates Ministry of Foreign Relations & International Cooperation|accessdate=20 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920123016/https://www.mofa.gov.ae/EN/DiplomaticMissions/Embassies/Tehran/Ambassador/Pages/Ambassador.aspx|archive-date=20 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n* Iran and United Arab Emirates both claims three islands in the [[Persian Gulf]] ([[Abu Musa]], [[Greater Tunb]], and [[Lesser Tunb]]).\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Iraq}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Iraq\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nThe [[Iraq invasion of Kuwait|Iraqi invasion and occupation of Kuwait]] were a shock to the UAE. For the UAE, the crisis over Kuwait demonstrated a lack of Arab unity on a critical Arab issue. The UAE joined the Arab states that opposed the Iraqi invasion and supported the use of force to compel Iraq's withdrawal of troops from Kuwait.<ref name=FROUAE>{{cite web|url=http://countrystudies.us/persian-gulf-states/91.htm|title=United Arab Emirates - Foreign Relations|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref> Prior to the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], the UAE opposed the US-led invasion.\n\nIn June 2008, the Iraqi government announced that the United Arab Emirates would send an ambassador to [[Baghdad]] within a few days. This would become the first Arab ambassador in Iraq since the kidnapping and murder of the Egyptian Ambassador [[Ihab el-Sherif]] in July 2005.  This announcement was made during a surprise visit by the United Arab Emirates' Foreign Minister [[Abdullah Bin Zayed Al Nahyan|Abdullah bin Zayed Al Nahyan]] to Baghdad on 5 June 2008.  This marked the first time a high-ranking official from a [[Arab States of the Persian Gulf|Gulf state]] visited Iraq since March 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Emirates to send envoy to Baghdad |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7437314.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |date=2008-06-05 |accessdate=2008-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=UAE to name ambassador to Baghdad |url=http://archive.gulfnews.com/articles/08/06/05/10218631.html |newspaper=[[Gulf News]] |date=2008-06-05 |accessdate=2008-06-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205074326/http://archive.gulfnews.com/articles/08/06/05/10218631.html |archivedate=2008-12-05 }}</ref>\n\nOn 31 July 2007 following Iraq victory of the [[Asian Cup]], Sheikh [[Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum]], Vice-President and Prime Minister of the UAE awarded the Iraq National football team 20 million Dhs, ($5.2 million) for capturing the Asian Cup for the first time in the country\u2019s history.<ref>{{cite web |title=Iraq football team awarded 5.5mn |url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/497138-iraq-football-team-awarded-55mn?ln=en |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120728225022/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/497138-iraq-football-team-awarded-55mn?ln=en |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-28 |date=2007-08-01 |accessdate=2008-11-30 }}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Israel}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Israel\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nNeither country have formal diplomatic relations with each other.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Japan}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\nDiplomatic relations between UAE and Japan were established as early as UAE's independence in December 1971.<ref name=MOFAJ>[http://www.mofa.go.jp/region/middle_e/uae/index.html Japan-United Arab Emirates Relations] Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Japan</ref> The two countries had always enjoyed friendly ties and trade between each other, exports from UAE to Japan include [[crude oil]] and [[natural gas]] and imports from Japan to UAE include cars and electronics items.<ref name=\"MOFAJ\"/> \n|-\n|{{Flag|Jordan}}\n|\n|Jordan was the first country to recognize UAE after forming the union in 1971. First commander in Chief in UAE military was Jordanian, and first commander in Zayed Military college was Jordanian as well. Making Jordan effectively one of a key partners of forming the UAE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.addustour.com/articles/1097263?s=e0539eda31b7aa6e3f170317f247a513|title=\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0631\u062f\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a .. \u0639\u0644\u0627\u0642\u0629 \u0645\u062a\u064a\u0646\u0629 \u0631\u0627\u0633\u062e\u0629|last=\u0627\u0644\u0642\u064a\u0633\u064a|first=\u0627\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645 \u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0645\u062c\u064a\u062f|website=\u062c\u0631\u064a\u062f\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0648\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0631\u062f\u0646\u064a\u0629|language=ar|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref>\nThe relationship between UAE and Jordan dates to the 1950s, before UAE gain independence and form the union. Jordan at the time used to aid UAE with educational, military, and health care missions, when UAE was still a barren desert.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nateqnews.com/NewsDetails.aspx?Id=21451|title=\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0641\u064a\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0631\u062a\u064a:\u0627\u0648\u0644 \u062f\u0648\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0639\u062a\u0631\u0641\u062a \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a\u062d\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0631\u062a\u064a \u0647\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0631\u062f\u0646|date=2017-12-02|website=\u0648\u0643\u0627\u0644\u0629 \u0646\u0627\u0637\u0642 \u0646\u064a\u0648\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u062e\u0628\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0629|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Kuwait}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Kuwait\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Kuwait has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Kuwait City]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Malaysia}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Malaysia\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nUnited Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Kuala Lumpur]], and Malaysia has an embassy in [[Abu Dhabi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kln.gov.my/perwakilan/abudhabi|title=Redirecting|accessdate=21 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221195512/http://www.kln.gov.my/perwakilan/abudhabi/|archive-date=2015-02-21|url-status=dead}}</ref> The countries established diplomatic relations in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/malaysia/mt_eco_cnt1.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-07-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081117180304/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/malaysia/mt_eco_cnt1.html |archivedate=2008-11-17 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005 Malaysia\u2019s export to the UAE stood at Dh7 billion. Main export items were gold and jewellery, wood products (furniture and parts), palm oil, petroleum products and electrical appliances. In 2007, trade between Malaysia and UAE was worth [[Malaysian ringgit|MYR]] 14.56 billion making UAE, Malaysia's largest trading partner in West Asia as well as Malaysia being the 10th largest exporter to UAE.<ref>http://www.bernama.com/bernama/v5/newsindex.php?id=340777</ref> In 2009, Malaysian ambassador Datuk Yahaya Abdul Jabar said total trade between Malaysia and UAE from January to November stood at RM19.5 billion. Malaysia's main exports to the UAE are jewellery, consumer electronics and palm oil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hailplaza.com|title=hailpaza.com|publisher=}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|North Korea }}||<!--Date started-->2007-09-19<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mobacle.blog.me/70022240636|title=\ubbf8\ub798\uc0ac\ud68c (FUSO) : \ub124\uc774\ubc84 \ube14\ub85c\uadf8|publisher=}}</ref> Relations ended 2007-10-12<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-missiles-emirates/uae-terminates-north-korean-diplomatic-mission-ends-visas-idUSKBN1CH247}}</ref>\n\nhttps://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-missiles-emirates/uae-terminates-north-korean-diplomatic-mission-ends-visas-idUSKBN1CH247\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Oman}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Oman\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Oman has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Muscat]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Pakistan}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Pakistan\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nPakistan and the UAE are very close allies with extremely close relations based on cultural affinities and shared [[Islam|faith]]. These relations date back to the UAE's formation in 1971, and have since developed into wide-ranging co-operation in various fields. UAE has been a major donor of economic assistance to Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pakobserver.net/200811/26/Editorial01.asp |title=Relations with UAE get wider, deeper |accessdate=December 26, 2008 |publisher=[[Pakistan Observer]] |date=November 26, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090626001001/http://pakobserver.net/200811/26/Editorial01.asp |archivedate=June 26, 2009 }}</ref> [[Shaikh Zayed International Airport (Rahim Yar Khan)|Sheikh Zayed International Airport]] in [[Rahim Yar Khan]], in the [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab province]] of Pakistan is an example of UAE's economic assistance as the late president and the founder of the UAE [[Sheikh Zayed]] donated the airport to the government of Pakistan.\n\nUAE has emerged as one of Pakistan's major economic and trading partners. A large number of Pakistani expatriates, numbering nearly 1.2 million are gainfully employed in UAE.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Qatar }}||'''Dipolmatic relations severed on 5 June 2017'''||See [[Qatar\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nIn 5 June 2017, the government of United Arab Emirates severed diplomatic ties with Qatar on accounts of [[Qatar and state-sponsored terrorism#2017 diplomatic crisis|Qatar's financial support for terrorism]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/06/05/middleeast/saudi-bahrain-egypt-uae-qatar-terror/index.html|title=Qatar rift: Saudi, UAE, Bahrain, Egypt cut diplomatic ties|publisher=CNN|date=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Russia}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Russia\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Russia has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Moscow]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Saudi Arabia}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Saudi Arabia\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Saudi Arabia has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a consulate-general in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Riyadh]] and a consulate-general in [[Jeddah]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|South Korea }}||<!--Date started-->18 June 1980<ref name=\"mofa.go.kr\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20150904015758/http://www.mofa.go.kr/ENG/countries/middleeast/countries/20070824/1_24424.jsp?menu=m_30_50 Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Republic of Korea-Middle East and Africa<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> ||\n* The establishment of diplomatic relations between the United Arab Emirates and the Republic of Korea began on 18 June 1980. \n* UAE is the 3rd largest exporter of oil to South Korea (108,000,000 barrels 2014).\n* The United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Seoul]].\n* South Korea has an embassy [[Abu Dhabi]].<ref name=\"mofa.go.kr\"/> \n|}\n\n==Europe==\nThe UAE\u2019s liberal climate towards foreign cooperation, investment and modernization have prompted extensive commercial ties with western countries, and subsequently resulting in even closer cultural relations.  The country remains a major global tourist and foreign direct investment destination but a few countries play a more significant role than the rest.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Albania}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Albania has an embassy in [[Abu Dhabi]].\n* United Arab Emirates is accredited to Albania from its embassy in [[Rome]], [[Italy]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Armenia}}||<!--Date started-->||\n* Diplomatic relations between Armenia and the UAE were established on June 25, 1998.\n* Armenia has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* The United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Yerevan]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Denmark}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Denmark\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Denmark has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates is accredited to Denmark from its embassy in [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|France}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[France\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nThe UAE\u2019s relationship with France has been strategically important as it negotiated a defence cooperation agreement and remains one of the country\u2019s primary providers of military material.<ref name=\"LOCCP:UAE\">Library of Congress Country Profile: UAE, http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/profiles/UAE.pdf</ref> France and the UAE have signed a defence cooperation agreement in order to diversity its procurement from solely the US.<ref name=\"LOCCP:UAE\"/> Culturally, as the [[Sorbonne]] and [[Louvre]] are both establishing extensions in the UAE,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2007-03-06-louvre-abu-dhabi_N.htm|title=Louvre museum to build branch in UAE - USATODAY.com|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref> a plan is in the works to recreate a miniature [[Lyon]] city in Dubai complete with public squares, restaurants and museums.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulfnews.com/Nation/Government/10214894.html|title=UAE and France share strong bilateral relations|accessdate=21 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202194826/http://www.gulfnews.com/nation/Government/10214894.html|archive-date=2008-12-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn May 25, 2009, the French president [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] visited the UAE, Abu Dhabi where he along with UAE's president H.H Sheikh Khalifa Bin Zayed Al Nahyan formally opened a French military base in the United Arab Emirates. This would become France's first permanent base in the Persian Gulf, hosting up to 500 French troops.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/8067600.stm|title=French President Sarkozy opens UAE base|accessdate=January 10, 2009 |work=BBC|date=May 26, 2009}}</ref> In addition to the inauguration of Peace Camp, Nicolas Sarkozy visited the site of a [[Louvre Abu Dhabi|Louvre Museum branch]] which France is opening in the United Arab Emirates. Sheikh Abdullah bin Zayed Al Nahyan, Minister of Foreign Affairs, said that the co-operation with France is a top priority for the UAE's foreign policy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gulfnews.com/nation/government/10317048.html|title=Relationship with France is top priority for UAE, Abdullah says|accessdate=January 10, 2009|work=Gulf News|date=May 26, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090528114021/http://www.gulfnews.com/nation/Government/10317048.html|archive-date=2009-05-28|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Georgia}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\nDiplomatic relations between [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and the UAE were initiated on 20 October 1992.<ref name=mofag>{{cite web|title=Relations Between Georgia and the United Arab Emirates|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Georgia)}}</ref> The countries are represented in each other through embassies.<ref name=mofag/> \n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Germany}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Germany\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nGerman exports amount to 5.84 billion Euros.<ref>[http://www.auswaertiges-amt.de/diplo/en/Laenderinformationen/01-Laender/VAE.html Federal Foreign Office of Germany] Country Profile UAE, October 2008</ref> German companies significantly contribute to the UAE\u2019s ongoing infrastructure projects and play a leading role in the country\u2019s alternative energy developments.<ref>[http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentID=2008103120686 \"UAE, Germany to cooperate in averting financial mayhem\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716184614/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentID=2008103120686 |date=July 16, 2011 }} ''Saudi Gazette''.</ref> Consequently, German [[Business Park]], an area designed to house several of the already seven hundred present companies and their logistical needs, is in the midst of construction.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dso.ae/en/news/german-business-park.html |title=Dubai Silicon Oasis Authority, Website News Release, October 2007 |access-date=2009-02-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090321172108/http://www.dso.ae/en/news/german-business-park.html |archive-date=2009-03-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Greece}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Greece\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Greece has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Athens]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Ireland}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Ireland has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Dublin]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Kosovo}}||14 October 2008<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wam.org.ae/servlet/Satellite?c=WamLocEnews&cid=1223546208865&p=1135099400124&pagename=WAM%2FWamLocEnews%2FW-T-LEN-FullNews |title=UAE recognises Kosovo |publisher=[[Emirates News Agency]] |date=2008-10-14 |accessdate=2008-10-14 |quote=In accordance with its firm support for the principle of the legitimate right of peoples to self-determination, the United Arab Emirates has announced its recognition of the Kosovo Republic as an independent and sovereign state. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081017065840/http://www.wam.org.ae/servlet/Satellite?c=WamLocEnews&cid=1223546208865&p=1135099400124&pagename=WAM%2FWamLocEnews%2FW-T-LEN-FullNews |archivedate=2008-10-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.africasia.com/services/news/newsitem.php?area=mideast&item=081014155526.3e2km83b.php|title=UAE recognises Kosovo|publisher=IC Publications|date=2008-10-14|accessdate=2008-10-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022221352/http://www.africasia.com/services/news/newsitem.php?area=mideast&item=081014155526.3e2km83b.php|archive-date=2008-10-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>||See [[Kosovo\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\n* Kosovo has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/kosovo-moldova-open-embassies-in-abu-dhabi-1.2220793|title=Kosovo, Moldova open embassies in Abu Dhabi|newspaper=Gulf News|date=13 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gazetaexpress.com/en/news/kosovo-opens-embassy-in-uae-174092/|title=Kosovo opens embassy in UAE|publisher=Gazeta Express|date=10 May 2018|access-date=15 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181216031421/https://www.gazetaexpress.com/en/news/kosovo-opens-embassy-in-uae-174092/|archive-date=16 December 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* United Arab Emirates is accredited to Kosovo from its embassy in [[Ankara]], [[Turkey]].\n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|North Macedonia}}||<!--Date started-->||\nNorth Macedonia has an embassy in [[Abu Dhabi]]<ref>[http://www.mfa.gov.mk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=429&Itemid=751&lang=en#dkpazija]</ref>. \n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Poland}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Poland has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Warsaw]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Serbia}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Serbia\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nRelations between Serbia and the United Arab Emirates have flourished in recent years. Serbia has an embassy in Abu Dhabi, and the UAE has an embassy in [[Belgrade]]. The UAE is now one of the top sources of FDI for Serbia.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Spain}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Spain has an embassy in Abu Dhabi and a commercial office in Dubai.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Madrid]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Ukraine}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* Ukraine has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Kiev]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|United Kingdom}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[United Arab Emirates\u2013United Kingdom relations]]\n\nTraditionally, links between the sheikhs of the lower Gulf and the United Kingdom were close as a result of a series of 19th-century maritime truces for the suppression of piracy. Since the British withdrew their military forces from the Persian Gulf in 1971, relations have remained friendly while the UAE has reorientated its foreign policy away from the former \"colonial\" relationship to one based on trade. Economically, the UAE is the UK\u2019s largest export market for non-military goods in the Middle East.<ref>British Foreign And Commonwealth Office, Country Profile: UAE; January 2009 {{cite web |url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/middle-east-north-africa/united-arab-emirates?profile=intRelations&pg=4 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081228153759/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/middle-east-north-africa/united-arab-emirates/?profile=intRelations&pg=4 |archivedate=2008-12-28 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Oceania==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Australia}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Australia\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n\nThe UAE and Australia have begun establishing closer relations, recently the UAE Minister of Economy, Sultan Bin Saeed Al Mansouri visited Australia along with the UAE delegation - discussion focused on the development of a strategic partnership, financial services, trade and investment.<ref>[http://www.wam.org.ae/servlet/Satellite?c=WamLocEnews&cid=1289993206373&p=1135099400124&pagename=WAM%2FWamLocEnews%2FW-T-LEN-FullNews UAE is strategic partner and a gateway for Australia to the Middle East, says Al Mansouri] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721081016/http://www.wam.org.ae/servlet/Satellite?c=WamLocEnews&cid=1289993206373&p=1135099400124&pagename=WAM%2FWamLocEnews%2FW-T-LEN-FullNews |date=July 21, 2011 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.wam.org.ae/servlet/Satellite?c=WamLocEnews&cid=1289993219934&p=1135099400124&pagename=WAM%2FWamLocEnews%2FW-T-LEN-FullNews UAE to forger closer economic ties Australia: Al-Mansouri] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721081034/http://www.wam.org.ae/servlet/Satellite?c=WamLocEnews&cid=1289993219934&p=1135099400124&pagename=WAM%2FWamLocEnews%2FW-T-LEN-FullNews |date=July 21, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/biz/inside.asp?xfile=/data/business/2011/April/business_April428.xml&section=business|title=UAE a gateway for Australia to ME: Mansouri - Khaleej Times|first=(Staff|last=Report)|publisher=}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|New Zealand}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\n* New Zealand has an embassy in Abu Dhabi.\n* United Arab Emirates has an embassy in [[Wellington]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Solomon Islands}}||<!--Date started-->2010||\nBoth countries established diplomatic relations on April 29, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wam.ae/en/details/1395228642109|title=UAE and Solomon Islands establish diplomatic relations|publisher=}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Tuvalu}}||<!--Date started-->||\n\nThe UAE and Tuvalu established diplomatic relations on 31 March 2010.<ref>[http://www.wam.org.ae/servlet/Satellite?c=WamLocEnews&cid=1267001043764&p=1135099400124&pagename=WAM%2FWamLocEnews%2FW-T-LEN-FullNews \"UAE and Tuvalu establish diplomatic relations\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203034816/http://www.wam.org.ae/servlet/Satellite?c=WamLocEnews&cid=1267001043764&p=1135099400124&pagename=WAM%2FWamLocEnews%2FW-T-LEN-FullNews |date=February 3, 2014 }} 31 March 2010 Link retrieved 01 April 2010</ref>\n|}\n\n==International disputes==\n{{See also|Territorial disputes in the Persian Gulf}}\n*Location and status of boundary with [[Saudi Arabia]] is not final, de facto boundary reflects 1974 agreement; no defined boundary with most of [[Oman]], but Administrative Line in far north;\n*Claims three islands in the [[Persian Gulf]] that are part of [[Iran]]'s territory: Lesser Tunb (called Tunb as Sughra in Arabic by UAE and Jazireh-ye Tonb-e Kuchak in Persian by Iran) and Greater Tunb (called Tunb al Kubra in Arabic by UAE and Jazireh-ye Tonb-e Bozorg in Persian by Iran);\n*Claims island in the Persian Gulf administered by Iran (called Abu Musa in Arabic by UAE and Jazireh-ye Abu Musa in Persian by Iran) - over which Iran has taken steps to exert unilateral control since 1992, including access restrictions and a military build-up on the island;\n\n==Illicit drugs==\nThe UAE plays a growing role as a [[drug trafficking]] center due to its proximity to southwest Asian producing countries and the bustling free trade zone in [[Dubai]]. As a result, the UAE has one of the strongest anti-drug law enforcement, and the penalty of drug possession is severe. The UAE ministry of foreign affairs warns tourists of UAE drug laws before entering the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tourists Warned of UAE Drug and Prescription Medication Laws |url=http://forum.virtualtourist.com/discussion-402276-1-1-Travel-0-0-Dubai-discussion.html |date=February 10, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of diplomatic missions in the United Arab Emirates]]\n* [[List of diplomatic missions of the United Arab Emirates]]