11 Major League Soccer season|2011]], [[2012 Major League Soccer season|2012]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MLS|hector-jimenez}}\n* {{Soccerway|hector-jimenez/132923}}\n\n{{Columbus Crew SC squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jimenez, Hector}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Association football utility players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American soccer players]]\n[[Category:American people of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:California Golden Bears men's soccer players]]\n[[Category:LA Galaxy players]]\n[[Category:Columbus Crew SC players]]\n[[Category:Soccer players from California]]\n[[Category:LA Galaxy draft picks]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer players]]\n[[Category:People from Bell Gardens, California]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:People from Huntington Park, California]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1012:b062:6c3d:ec68:cda6:1380:d29b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hector_Jim%C3%A9nez_(soccer)"}
{"title_page": "WrestleMania", "text_new": "{{About|the event series in general|the first edition of the event|WrestleMania I|other uses|WrestleMania (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-semi-indef|small=yes}}\n{{short description|WWE pay-per-view series}}\n\n{{Infobox wrestling PPV series\n|name = WrestleMania \n|image = Wrestlemania_Neutral_Logo.svg\n|image_size = 250px\n|caption = The official WrestleMania logo\n|alt = The official WrestleMania logo\n|nicknames = ''\"The Grandest Stage of Them All\"<br/>\"The Showcase of the Immortals\"<br/>\"The Show of Shows\"<br/>\"The Greatest Spectacle in Sports Entertainment\"''<br/>''\"The Super Bowl of Sports Entertainment\"''<br/>''\"The Granddaddy of Them All\"''\n|createdby = [[Vince McMahon]]\n|promotions = [[WWE]]\n|brands = [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]]<br>(2003\u20132011, 2017\u2013present)<br>[[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]]<br>(2003\u20132011, 2017\u2013present)<br>[[205 Live (WWE brand)|205 Live]]<br>(2019)<br>[[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]]<br>(2020\u2013present)<br>[[ECW (WWE brand)|ECW]]<br>(2007\u20132009)\n|firstevent = [[WrestleMania I]]\n|gimmick = \n}}\n\n'''WrestleMania''' is a [[professional wrestling]] event produced annually between mid-March to mid-April by [[WWE]], an American [[professional wrestling promotion]] based in [[Stamford, Connecticut]]. WWE first produced the event in 1985 and has since produced 36 editions, with the [[WrestleMania 36|most recent]] having been held in [[Orlando, Florida]] on March 25\u201326, 2020 ([[Broadcast delay|aired]] April 4\u20135). WrestleMania, WWE's flagship event, airs on [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) and the [[WWE Network]] and is the most successful and longest-running professional wrestling event in history. It contributes to the worldwide commercial success of WWE through media, merchandise, and shows. WrestleMania was conceptualized by WWE owner [[Vince McMahon]], while long time WWE ring announcer and [[WWE Hall of Fame|Hall of Famer]] [[Howard Finkel]] is credited with devising the name \"WrestleMania\" in 1984.\n\nWrestleMania's widespread success helped transform professional wrestling. The event has facilitated the rise to stardom of several top WWE wrestlers. Celebrities such as [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Cyndi Lauper]], [[Muhammad Ali]], [[Mr. T]], [[Alice Cooper]], [[Lawrence Taylor]], [[Pamela Anderson]], [[Mike Tyson]], [[Donald Trump]], [[Floyd Mayweather, Jr.]], [[Pete Rose]], [[Burt Reynolds]], [[Mickey Rourke]], [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Sean Combs|Sean \"Diddy\" Combs]], [[Kid Rock]], [[Fred Durst]], [[Ozzy Osbourne]], [[Ronda Rousey]], [[Rob Gronkowski]], and [[Shaquille O'Neal]] have participated or made special appearances within the events.\n\nThe [[WrestleMania I|first WrestleMania]] was held in [[Madison Square Garden]] in [[New York City]]; the 10th and 20th editions were also held there. [[WrestleMania III]] in the [[Detroit]] suburb of [[Pontiac, Michigan]] was the highest-attended indoor sports event in the world, with 93,173 fans in attendance. The record stood until February 14, 2010, when the [[2010 NBA All-Star Game]] broke the indoor sporting event record with an attendance of 108,713 at Cowboys Stadium, since renamed [[AT&T Stadium]], in [[Arlington, Texas]].<ref name=\"AP recap\">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=300214032|title=East wins in front of biggest crowd to watch hoops game |publisher=ESPN|date=February 14, 2010|accessdate=February 15, 2010}}</ref> In 2016, WrestleMania 32 surpassed WrestleMania III as the highest-attended professional wrestling event ever held in America, with 101,763 fans in attendance at AT&T Stadium, although the company revealed that attendance figures are manipulated for marketing purposes through investor calls. All editions of the event have been hosted in North American cities, with 34 in the [[United States]] and two in [[Canada]].\n\n==Organization==\n[[File:WrestleMania 32 2016-04-03 18-55-46 ILCE-6000 9123 DxO (27799110291).jpg|thumb|right|[[AT&T Stadium]] during [[WrestleMania 32]].]]\nMost WrestleMania events have taken place in large stadiums in large cities, with some in sports arenas. The most-attended events include [[WrestleMania III]] (93,173) in [[Pontiac, Michigan|Pontiac]], [[WrestleMania VI]] (67,678) in [[Toronto]], [[WrestleMania VIII]] (62,167) in [[Indianapolis]], [[WrestleMania X-Seven]] (67,925) in [[Houston]], [[WrestleMania X8]] (68,237) also in Toronto, [[WrestleMania XIX]] (54,097) in [[Seattle]], [[WrestleMania 23]] (80,103) in [[Detroit]], [[WrestleMania XXIV]] (74,635) in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], [[WrestleMania XXV]] (72,744) also in Houston, [[WrestleMania XXVI]] (72,219) in [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[WrestleMania XXVII]] (71,617) in [[Atlanta]], [[WrestleMania XXVIII]] (78,363) in [[Miami]], [[WrestleMania 29]] (80,676) in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey|East Rutherford]], [[WrestleMania XXX]] (75,167) in [[New Orleans]], [[WrestleMania 31]] (76,976) in [[Santa Clara, California|Santa Clara]], and [[WrestleMania 32]] (101,763) in [[Arlington, Texas|Arlington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2010/2010_3_28.jsp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-03-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403082320/http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2010/2010_3_28.jsp |archivedate=2010-04-03 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.universityofphoenixstadium.com/index.php?page%3Dpress%26section%3Dstadium_features%26feature_id%3D69 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-08-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717164401/http://www.universityofphoenixstadium.com/index.php?page=press&section=stadium_features&feature_id=69 |archivedate=2011-07-17 }}</ref> Since moving to large stadiums and running [[WrestleMania Axxess]], the event produces a local economy boost for the host cities.<ref>{{cite news |last=Caldwell |first=James |url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_31086.shtml |title=Houston Chronicle homepage features cover-story on WrestleMania 25 and impact on local economy |work=Pro Wrestling Torch |date=1 April 2009 |accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hanks |first=Douglas |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/business/article1943661.html |title=WWE says Wrestlemania brought $103 million to South Florida |work=[[Miami Herald]] |date=15 October 2012 |accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jessop |first=Alicia |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/aliciajessop/2013/04/07/630/ |title=WrestleMania Brings 70,000 Fans And Multi-Million Dollar Economic Impact To The New York Metropolitan Area |work=[[Forbes]] |date=7 April 2013 |accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Graser |first=Marc |url=https://variety.com/2014/biz/news/wrestlemania-celebrates-30-years-as-wwe-pins-down-big-deals-bright-future-1201151246/ |title=\u2018WrestleMania\u2019 Celebrates 30 Years as WWE Pins Down Big Deals, Bright Future |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=3 April 2014 |accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nWrestleMania centers on the main event matches, primarily for the [[WWE Championship]] - and additional world titles, such as the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]] (2003-2013) and the [[WWE Universal Championship]] (since 2017) - as well as matches involving celebrities such as [[American football]]er [[Lawrence Taylor]] or actor [[Mr. T]]. Other WWE championships are also contested for, while the [[Card (sports)|match card]] also includes gimmick matches and matches involving personal feuds.\n\nSince 1993, the winner of the annual [[Royal Rumble]] match has been able to receive a guaranteed WWE Championship match at the same year's WrestleMania. With the introduction of the World Heavyweight Championship in 2002, the winner was also given the option to choose between the world title or the WWE championship. The creation of the [[ECW (WWE brand)|ECW brand]] in June 2006 gave the Rumble winner a third option: to choose to challenge for the [[ECW World Championship]]. This option was made available from 2007 until the brand was retired in 2010. However, this option was never chosen.<ref name=ecwtitle>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/02052007/|title=Tickets punched for WrestleMania|first=Brett|last=Hoffman|publisher=WWE|accessdate=2007-12-05|date=2007-02-05}}</ref> The brand split ended in 2011 and the WWE and World Heavyweight Championships were unified in 2013, leaving the former as the only title to challenge for until the reintroduction of the brand split in 2016, which added the WWE Universal Championship as a choice. A women's Royal Rumble match was introduced in 2018, and the winner has the option of challenging for either the [[WWE Raw Women's Championship]] or [[WWE SmackDown Women's Championship]].\n\n[[WrestleMania 21]] saw the introduction of the [[Money in the Bank ladder match]]. This match features six to ten participants and took place at six WrestleManias between 2005 and 2010 before becoming the headline match of its own [[pay-per-view]] event, [[WWE Money in the Bank|Money in the Bank]] which incorporated the use of two Money in the Bank ladder matches for both respective WWE brands, [[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown]] and [[WWE Raw|Raw]]. The participant who retrieves the briefcase suspended above the ring wins a contract, which guarantees a world title match at the time and place of the winner's choosing for up to one year, including the following year's WrestleMania. This lasted until 2010 when the Money in the Bank pay per view was introduced and thus the Money in the Bank ladder match was retired from WrestleMania.<ref name=\"MITB1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/2008/matches/6464426/results/|accessdate=2008-05-23|title=Results:Money in the Bank ladder match| publisher=[[WWE]]|date=2008-03-30}}</ref>\n\n[[Forbes]] named WrestleMania one of the world's most valuable sports event brands from 2014 to 2017, ranking it sixth with a brand value of US$195 million in 2017 behind the [[Super Bowl]], [[Summer Olympics]], [[Winter Olympics]], the [[FIFA World Cup]], and the [[NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Final Four]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/59e62ee431358e542c03d5be/6-wrestlemania/|title=Forbes Fab 40 2017|magazine=Forbes|accessdate=24 October 2017|date=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Commentators===\nFor five of the first six WrestleManias [[Gorilla Monsoon]] and [[Jesse Ventura]] served as the color commentators (the exception being WrestleMania 2, which was split among three venues and had Monsoon, Ventura, and Vince McMahon split up with guest commentators), while [[Bobby Heenan]], [[Gene Okerlund]], [[Lord Alfred Hayes]] and others filled guest roles. For WrestleMania VII and VIII, Monsoon and Heenan provided color commentary. In the mid to late 1990s the commentator team comprised [[Vince McMahon]], [[Jim Ross]], and [[Jerry Lawler]]. Since the brand separation in 2002, matches from the [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]] brand have been called by Ross and Lawler; the [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]] matches called by [[Michael Cole (wrestling)|Michael Cole]], [[Tazz]], [[John Layfield|John \"Bradshaw\" Layfield]] and [[Jonathan Coachman]], and from 2006 to 2010, the [[ECW (WWE brand)|ECW]] matches called by [[Joey Styles]] and Tazz. At WrestleMania XXV the first three-man inter-brand commentary team since the [[WWE Brand Extension]] was used, and consisted of Jim Ross, Jerry \"The King\" Lawler, and [[Michael Cole (wrestling)|Michael Cole]]. The following year Jim Ross was replaced by [[Matt Striker]] at WrestleMania XXVI. At WrestleMania XXVII Jim Ross returned to commentate, along with [[Josh Mathews]] and new ''SmackDown'' color commentator [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]]; the sudden change of commentary was due to a singles match between regular commentators Michael Cole and Lawler. [[Howard Finkel]], who is credited with coming up with the name \"WrestleMania\" in 1984,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radio.thescore.com/episodes/howard-finkel-raw-03282011|title=Howard Finkel \u2013 R.A.W. March 28, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120729100940/http://radio.thescore.com/episodes/howard-finkel-raw-03282011|archivedate=July 29, 2012}}</ref> has served as the long-standing ring-announcer and has appeared at every event except [[WrestleMania 33]], but since the WWE Brand Extension, [[Lilian Garcia]], [[Tony Chimel]] and [[Justin Roberts]] have taken over as announcers for their respective brand matches. Four French commentators were at ringside: Jean Brassard and [[Raymond Rougeau]] ([[WrestleMania 13]]), Phillippe Ch\u00e9reau and Christophe Agius ([[WrestleMania XXX]], [[WrestleMania 31]], [[WrestleMania 32]], and [[WrestleMania 33]]).\n\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:1301 height:auto barincrement:20\nPlotArea = left:105 bottom:60 top:0 right:15\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat = mm/dd/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/1985 till:{{#time:m/d/Y}}\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:horizontal position:bottom\nScaleMajor = increment:1 start:1985\n\nColors =\n id:comm value:red legend:Commentator\n id:cocomm value:green legend:Color_commentator\n id:guest value:yellow legend:Guest_commentator\n id:esp value:orange legend:Spanish_commentator\n id:espc value:blue legend:Spanish_color_commentator\n id:bars value:gray(0.9)\n\nBackgroundColors = bars:bars\n\nLineData =\n at:03/31/1985 color:black layer:back\n at:04/07/1986 color:black layer:back\n at:03/29/1987 color:black layer:back\n at:03/27/1988 color:black layer:back\n at:04/02/1989 color:black layer:back\n at:04/01/1990 color:black layer:back\n at:03/24/1991 color:black layer:back\n at:04/05/1992 color:black layer:back\n at:04/04/1993 color:black layer:back\n at:03/20/1994 color:black layer:back\n at:04/02/1995 color:black layer:back\n at:03/31/1996 color:black layer:back\n at:03/23/1997 color:black layer: